INSERT INTO public.quiz_questions (level_id, topic_tag, question, options, correct_index, explanation)
VALUES
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm is evaluating two potential targets. Company A generates €30M EBITDA with 85% recurring subscription revenue and 5% annual capex. Company B generates €30M EBITDA with project-based revenue tied to the construction cycle and 15% annual capex. Which is the stronger LBO candidate and why?', '["Company B — higher capex means more tangible assets to serve as debt collateral","Company A — stable recurring revenue and low capex produce predictable free cash flow to service debt","Both are equally suitable since they have identical EBITDA","Company B — cyclical businesses typically command higher exit multiples"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LBO candidates need stable, predictable cash flows because debt service is non-negotiable. Recurring subscription revenue and low capex produce reliable free cash flow. Cyclical, project-based businesses with high capex are poor LBO candidates because a downturn can trigger covenant breach while the debt load remains constant.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm has signed a Letter of Intent on a €300M acquisition with a 60-day exclusivity period. Three weeks into diligence, a competitor approaches the seller with a higher offer. What does the exclusivity provision allow or require?', '["The seller must automatically accept the higher offer and terminate negotiations with the PE firm","The seller is contractually prohibited from negotiating with the competitor during the exclusivity window","The PE firm must match the higher offer or lose its position","Exclusivity provisions are non-binding and the seller can negotiate freely"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Exclusivity provisions in LOIs legally prevent the seller from negotiating with other parties during the specified window — typically 30–60 days. This protects the buyer''s diligence investment. While LOIs are generally non-binding on price and terms, exclusivity provisions are binding and enforceable.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm acquires a company for $500M using $175M equity and $325M debt. After 5 years, the business is sold for $600M. During the hold period, $100M of debt was repaid. What is the approximate equity return?', '["1.2x — matching the enterprise value appreciation from $500M to $600M","2.0x — driven primarily by debt paydown even though enterprise value grew modestly","3.4x — because leverage amplifies the small enterprise value increase","The equity was lost because remaining debt exceeds the sale proceeds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Exit equity = $600M (EV) – $225M (remaining debt after $100M paydown) = $375M. MOIC = $375M / $175M ≈ 2.1x. This illustrates the leverage effect: even a modest 20% enterprise value increase produces a doubling of equity value when combined with significant debt paydown.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE-backed company has €60M of EBITDA and €360M of debt structured across senior secured (€240M at 5%), second lien (€80M at 8%), and mezzanine (€40M at 11%). What is the company''s leverage ratio, and what does this indicate?', '["4.0x — a conservative leverage level typical of investment-grade corporate structures","6.0x — a typical leveraged buyout capital structure for a stable business","9.5x — an extremely aggressive structure that would fail most covenant tests","Cannot be calculated without knowing the equity contribution"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Leverage ratio = Total Debt / EBITDA = €360M / €60M = 6.0x. This is a typical LBO entry leverage for a stable, cash-generative business. Investment-grade corporates usually carry 2-3x leverage; LBOs range from 4-7x depending on business quality and credit market conditions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'At its most basic, what is a leveraged buyout (LBO)?', '["An acquisition funded entirely with equity capital from a PE fund","An acquisition where a PE fund uses a combination of equity and significant borrowed money to buy a company, with the debt typically secured against the target''s assets","A hostile takeover of a publicly listed company","A merger between two similarly sized private companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'An LBO uses a combination of equity (from the PE fund) and debt (from lenders) to acquire a company. The debt is typically secured against the target''s assets and repaid from its cash flows. This structure amplifies equity returns when the business performs but concentrates risk if it does not.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A typical mid-market European LBO uses approximately what capital structure split between equity and debt?', '["90% equity, 10% debt","30-45% equity, 55-70% debt","10% equity, 90% debt","100% equity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Most mid-market LBOs finance deals with 30-45% equity and 55-70% debt. The exact ratio depends on business quality, credit conditions, and sector. Business with highly stable cash flows may support higher leverage; more volatile businesses require more equity. European deals have historically used slightly more conservative ratios than US deals.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'In an LBO, debt is typically repaid over the hold period using what source of funds?', '["Additional equity contributions from the PE fund","The target company''s own free cash flow","Proceeds from asset sales at the PE fund level","Interest income earned on the company''s cash balance"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The target company''s free cash flow is the primary source of debt service. The company generates EBITDA, pays interest on the debt, funds capex and working capital, and uses remaining cash to amortise debt or accumulate on the balance sheet. This is why LBO candidates must have predictable, sustainable cash flow — debt service is non-negotiable.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm is evaluating a business with €25M EBITDA and €4M annual capex. Approximately how much free cash flow is available for debt service, assuming a 25% tax rate and €1M working capital increase?', '["€25M — EBITDA represents available cash flow","Approximately €15M — EBITDA less taxes, capex, and working capital","€4M — only capex should be deducted","€21M — EBITDA less capex only"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Free cash flow before debt service ≈ EBITDA – cash taxes – capex – working capital change. Roughly: €25M – €6M (25% tax assumption) – €4M capex – €1M WC = €14-15M. This FCF figure determines how much debt the business can safely carry, not EBITDA alone. High-quality LBOs focus on FCF conversion, not just headline EBITDA.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE fund is evaluating a target acquisition. During the initial screening phase, which of the following information sources would typically be reviewed FIRST, before formal due diligence begins?', '["Full audited financial statements with all supporting documentation","A teaser or confidential information memorandum (CIM) prepared by the sell-side adviser, providing high-level business overview and key financials","Customer contracts and supplier agreements","Employee records and compensation details"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The teaser (1-2 pages, anonymised) and subsequent CIM (30-100+ pages, named) are the first documents PE firms review in an auction process. They provide a high-level overview of the business, market, financials, and investment highlights. Detailed diligence documents (full financials, contracts, operational data) are only shared after NDA execution and initial bid selection.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A seller running a competitive auction invites PE firms to submit ''indicative bids'' after initial review of the CIM. How do indicative bids typically differ from binding bids?', '["Indicative bids are legally enforceable; binding bids are not","Indicative bids express interest at a price range based on limited information; binding bids are submitted after full due diligence and include firm price and committed financing","Indicative bids must exceed binding bids to qualify","There is no practical difference between the two"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Indicative bids are non-binding expressions of interest at a preliminary price range, submitted based on limited information (CIM and a management presentation). They narrow the field to a shortlist. Binding bids are submitted after full due diligence, include firm pricing and committed debt financing, and are enforceable if accepted by the seller subject to SPA negotiation.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm is considering an acquisition sourced through a proprietary relationship rather than a competitive auction. What pricing dynamic does this typically create compared to a formal auction?', '["Proprietary deals always command higher prices than auction deals","Proprietary deals often benefit the buyer through reduced competitive tension, less pricing pressure, and more flexibility in process","Proprietary deals bypass all due diligence requirements","Proprietary deals cannot be financed with debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Proprietary deals — where the PE firm negotiates directly with the seller without a formal competitive process — typically produce better pricing and terms for the buyer. Without competing bids, the seller lacks pricing pressure; the buyer can structure a process on its timeline; and the buyer often gains access to management before pricing is locked. This is why PE firms invest heavily in relationship-based sourcing.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'In a typical M&A transaction, what is the distinction between ''signing'' and ''closing''?', '["Signing and closing are the same event","Signing is when the definitive agreements (SPA) are executed; closing is when the transaction actually completes, which may be days or months later after conditions are satisfied","Signing is when money changes hands; closing is the legal filing","Signing occurs before diligence; closing occurs after"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Signing is the execution of definitive agreements (typically the SPA) — the parties are now contractually bound. Closing is the completion of the transaction: money transfers, shares change hands, and the business is legally transferred. Between signing and closing, conditions must be satisfied (regulatory approvals, financing commitments, sometimes specific operational milestones). The gap can be days (simple deals) to many months (complex or regulated deals).'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm acquires a business at 10x EBITDA. Five years later, the business is sold at 10x EBITDA with no change in multiple. EBITDA is flat throughout the hold period. How could the deal still generate strong equity returns?', '["It cannot — flat EBITDA and flat multiple mean no return","Debt paydown during the hold period increases the equity''s share of enterprise value, generating returns even without operational improvement","The deal would lose money in this scenario","Dividend recapitalisations are the only source of return"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Even without EBITDA growth or multiple expansion, debt paydown increases the equity value at exit. Example: Entry at €100M EV (€40M equity, €60M debt). Exit at €100M EV with €30M debt repaid = €70M equity (1.75x return on €40M). In practice, PE firms rarely rely solely on this lever — it is a backstop for returns even when other drivers disappoint.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'Why do LBO capital structures amplify equity returns compared to all-equity acquisitions?', '["Debt is cheaper than equity, reducing the company''s cost of capital","Leverage concentrates the ownership stake of equity holders, so business value appreciation flows disproportionately to them while debt remains fixed","Debt holders are entitled to share in equity upside","Tax regulations automatically increase returns on leveraged deals"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Leverage amplifies returns through a simple mechanic: debt is a fixed claim that does not share in upside. If the business''s enterprise value grows, the debt still owes the same amount while the equity captures the full value increase. A 20% rise in EV can translate to 50%+ equity returns depending on leverage. The same mechanic amplifies losses when the business declines.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm is stress-testing its LBO model. The base case projects 8% annual EBITDA growth; the downside scenario holds EBITDA flat. In the downside case, the highest-risk outcome for equity holders is:', '["The business will generate no profit","Debt service may consume most or all of the business''s free cash flow, increasing the risk of covenant breach and potential equity wipeout if performance deteriorates further","The business will need additional equity from the PE fund","Lenders will automatically seize the business"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Flat EBITDA combined with fixed debt service consumes the margin of safety. If performance deteriorates further, covenants may be breached (giving lenders intervention rights), refinancing becomes uncertain, and in severe cases equity can be wiped out while lenders recover through restructuring. This downside asymmetry — unlimited upside but bounded loss at equity — is why entry leverage and business quality matter so much.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A lender evaluating an LBO financing request focuses heavily on the interest coverage ratio. What does this metric measure, and why does it matter?', '["It measures the company''s gross margin; it matters because lenders prefer high-margin businesses","It measures EBITDA divided by interest expense; it matters because lenders want comfort that cash flow comfortably covers interest obligations with margin for error","It measures the company''s market share; it matters because lenders prefer dominant companies","It measures the age of the company''s debt"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Interest coverage = EBITDA / Interest Expense. Lenders want comfort that the business generates cash flow comfortably exceeding its interest obligations. Typical minimums are 2.0-2.5x for LBO debt; weaker coverage indicates elevated default risk. Interest coverage is often included as a financial covenant, with breach triggering default and requiring renegotiation.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm''s LBO model shows the business will generate €20M of free cash flow annually, sufficient to service €8M of interest and make €6M of mandatory debt amortisation. What happens to the remaining €6M?', '["It must be returned to the PE fund as a dividend","It can be used for various purposes including voluntary debt prepayment (cash sweep), accumulation on the balance sheet, bolt-on acquisitions, or later distributions to the PE fund","It is automatically paid to management as a bonus","It must be paid as additional taxes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Excess cash flow above mandatory debt service is discretionary. Loan agreements typically include a ''cash sweep'' that redirects a percentage (often 50-75%) to voluntary debt prepayment. Remaining cash may fund bolt-on acquisitions, accumulate on the balance sheet for flexibility, or — if permitted by the credit agreement — be distributed to the PE fund through dividend recapitalisation.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'In an LBO, debt amortisation can be structured as either ''amortising'' or ''bullet'' repayment. What distinguishes these structures?', '["Amortising debt is repaid in equal instalments over the term; bullet debt is repaid in full at maturity with minimal interim amortisation","Both structures are identical","Amortising debt charges higher interest; bullet debt is interest-free","Amortising debt matures in one year; bullet debt has no maturity"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Amortising debt requires regular principal repayments over the term (e.g., quarterly payments until full amortisation at maturity). Bullet debt makes minimal or no principal repayments during the term, with full principal due at maturity. LBO Term Loan B (the most common leveraged loan) is typically bullet (nominal 1% per year amortisation, 99% at maturity), allowing maximum cash flow retention during the hold period.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm evaluates an LBO opportunity and identifies €5M in ''run-rate savings'' from a planned cost programme. How should this figure typically be treated in the model?', '["Added to day-one EBITDA without adjustment","Phased in over 12-24 months during the hold, with implementation costs and risk-adjustment for achievement uncertainty","Excluded entirely from the analysis","Doubled to reflect upside potential"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Run-rate savings represent projected future savings from a programme that has not yet been fully implemented. Sophisticated LBO models phase these in over 12-24 months, include one-time implementation costs (severance, consulting fees, IT changes), and often apply a haircut to the target (achieving 70-80% of planned savings) to reflect execution uncertainty. Adding projected savings directly to day-one EBITDA inflates the entry multiple.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'Which of the following business characteristics is MOST important for a business to be a strong LBO candidate?', '["High growth rate exceeding 30% annually","Predictable, stable free cash flow generation sufficient to service debt","A founder who will remain for decades","Operations in multiple geographies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The defining LBO candidate feature is predictable, stable free cash flow — because debt service is non-negotiable. Growth, management continuity, and geographic diversification are positive but secondary. A slow-growing business with rock-solid recurring cash flows is a better LBO candidate than a fast-growing business with volatile earnings. This is why subscription businesses, consumer staples, and industrial services have been prime LBO targets for decades.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm pays €200M for a business generating €25M EBITDA. What is the entry multiple, and how does this compare to typical mid-market LBO multiples?', '["8.0x — typical of mid-market transactions in many sectors","12.5x — typical of small-cap public companies","4.0x — unusually low, suggesting a distressed situation","Cannot be calculated from the information given"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Entry multiple = EV / EBITDA = €200M / €25M = 8.0x. This is within the typical range for mid-market LBOs (6-11x depending on sector, growth, quality, and market conditions). Software and high-growth sectors trade higher; cyclical or commoditised businesses trade lower. The entry multiple sets the target for value creation — typically the PE firm seeks exit at a similar or expanded multiple.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'Between the signing of an SPA and the closing of the transaction, what is typically required to happen?', '["Nothing — closing follows automatically from signing","Conditions precedent must be satisfied: regulatory approvals (competition, foreign investment), financing commitments confirmed, sometimes employee or customer consents obtained","The seller must repurchase the business from itself","All employees must resign"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Between signing and closing, conditions precedent must be satisfied. Common conditions: antitrust/competition clearance, foreign investment screening approval, sector-specific regulatory approval (financial services, healthcare), third-party consents on critical contracts, and confirmation of debt financing. The gap can be anywhere from 30 days to 12+ months depending on complexity. Deals can fall apart during this period if conditions fail.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm is acquiring a family-owned business where the founder will stay on as CEO. The structure includes €20M of ''rollover equity'' where the founder retains a stake in the new company. What is the purpose of rollover equity?', '["To reduce the PE firm''s equity investment","To align the founder''s financial interests with post-acquisition value creation, ensuring commitment and continuity","To avoid paying the founder any cash at closing","To comply with regulatory requirements"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Rollover equity — where the seller retains a meaningful equity stake in the new PE-backed entity — aligns continuing management''s financial interests with post-acquisition performance. A founder who rolls 20-30% into the new company is materially invested in the success of the value creation plan. This is particularly important when the founder remains as CEO or in another executive role where their ongoing contribution matters.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm''s Share Purchase Agreement (SPA) contains detailed ''warranties and representations'' from the seller. What purpose do these serve?', '["They guarantee the buyer will achieve specific returns","They allocate risk between buyer and seller for the business''s condition at closing, enabling the buyer to claim damages if a warranty is breached after closing","They replace the need for due diligence","They set the purchase price of the deal"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Warranties and representations are contractual statements by the seller about the business''s condition: financial statements are accurate, no undisclosed litigation, no material breach of contracts, tax compliance, employment matters disclosed, and so on. If a warranty proves false after closing, the buyer can claim damages (subject to disclosure and limitations). W&R allocate risk and supplement due diligence — they do not replace it.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A buyer and seller disagree on the target''s valuation. The buyer believes the business is worth €80M; the seller believes €100M. What deal structure might bridge this gap?', '["The buyer must simply pay the seller''s price","An earnout provision, where additional consideration (up to €20M) is paid to the seller if the business achieves specified performance milestones post-closing","The deal cannot proceed without perfect price agreement","The buyer and seller split ownership 50/50"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Earnouts bridge valuation gaps by tying a portion of consideration to post-closing performance. If the seller is right about the business''s prospects, they earn the full €100M; if the buyer is right, they only pay €80M. Earnouts are common in owner-led deals and growth situations but create complexity (metric definitions, measurement disputes, buyer control questions) that can lead to post-closing conflict.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'At closing of an M&A transaction, a portion of the purchase price is often held in ''escrow'' for a period of 12-24 months. What is the purpose?', '["To give the seller time to leave the business gradually","To provide a pre-funded source of recovery for the buyer if warranty claims or indemnity claims arise post-closing","To pay legal fees gradually","To avoid antitrust regulations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Escrow (typically 5-15% of purchase price) provides the buyer with a pre-funded source of recovery for warranty breaches, indemnity claims, or working capital adjustments identified after closing. Instead of suing the seller to recover damages, the buyer claims against the escrow. Escrow periods typically run 12-24 months, releasing gradually as claim periods expire.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm''s typical hold period for a buyout investment is 5-7 years. What three-phase framework describes how value is created during this period?', '["Borrow → pay dividends → sell","Buy → transform → sell (acquire the business, execute the value creation plan, exit to realise returns)","Fund → list on public markets → trade","Merge → split → liquidate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The PE value creation model follows three phases: BUY (identify and acquire the target at an attractive price); TRANSFORM (execute the 100-day plan, drive operational improvement, complete bolt-on acquisitions, optimise capital structure); SELL (exit to a strategic buyer, financial buyer, or through IPO, realising returns for LPs and GP). This buy-improve-sell cycle is fundamental to how PE generates returns.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'The first 100 days after a PE acquisition are considered particularly critical. What typically happens during this period?', '["The PE firm waits to observe the business before making changes","The PE firm and management execute immediate priorities: KPI tracking, quick wins, organisational assessment, cash management, and setting up the value creation plan for longer-term initiatives","The business is listed on a public stock exchange","All existing management is replaced"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The 100-day plan focuses on actions that can be initiated immediately: establishing monthly KPI reporting, implementing cash management discipline, conducting management assessment, executing quick-win initiatives (pricing, procurement), and setting up the longer-term value creation plan. Speed matters — momentum in the first 100 days shapes the entire hold period''s trajectory.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm acquires a business with the intention of building a ''platform'' and adding multiple bolt-on acquisitions. Why can bolt-ons generate attractive returns even without operational improvement?', '["Bolt-ons are exempt from taxes","Bolt-ons are typically acquired at lower multiples than the platform, producing ''multiple arbitrage'' when the combined entity is sold at the platform''s higher exit multiple","Bolt-ons never require integration costs","Bolt-ons are always paid for in equity rather than cash"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Multiple arbitrage: if the platform is acquired at 10x EBITDA and bolt-ons are acquired at 5-7x, the bolt-on EBITDA is re-valued at the platform''s exit multiple (say 10-11x) when the combined entity is sold. This multiple expansion on acquired EBITDA is a reliable source of return even if no operational improvement occurs. Combined with synergies and operational improvement, buy-and-build can produce extraordinary returns.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE fund''s 10-year life typically follows a J-curve pattern in reported returns. What does this mean and why does it occur?', '["Returns are constant throughout the fund life","Returns are initially negative due to fees and slow value realisation, then accelerate sharply in years 4-8 as exits occur and portfolio companies mature","Returns are highest in the first year","Returns are unpredictable and random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The J-curve: in the first 2-3 years, fees are charged on committed capital while portfolio companies are being acquired and just starting their value creation journey — producing negative reported returns. From years 4-8, portfolio companies mature and exits begin, driving strong positive returns. The shape resembles a ''J'' on a graph. Sophisticated LPs understand and plan for the J-curve; unsophisticated evaluators mistake early losses for fund failure.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm typically seeks majority control (51%+) of its portfolio companies rather than minority stakes. Why is control so central to the PE model?', '["Minority stakes are prohibited by regulation","Control enables the PE firm to implement its value creation plan — replacing management, changing strategy, optimising capital structure, and driving exits — without dependence on other shareholders'' consent","Minority stakes cannot be leveraged","Control provides higher tax benefits than minority positions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Majority control is essential to executing the PE playbook: replacing underperforming management, implementing cost programmes, completing bolt-on acquisitions, optimising capital structure, and deciding on exit timing — all without needing approval from minority shareholders. Minority investments exist in PE (growth equity, structured equity) but operate under different economics because the investor lacks the control needed for traditional value creation.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A large LBO acquisition is subject to competition law review in multiple jurisdictions before it can close. What is the typical concern of competition regulators?', '["The PE fund''s internal governance structure","Whether the combination of buyer and target creates excessive market concentration that could harm consumers through higher prices or reduced choice","The PE fund''s profitability","The target company''s CEO compensation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Competition law focuses on whether a transaction creates or strengthens market dominance that could harm competition (and therefore consumers). In PE deals, concerns typically arise from bolt-on acquisitions combining competitors in fragmented markets, or when a PE firm owns competing businesses in the same sector across different funds. Clearance is required above specified thresholds; regulators can require divestitures or block deals entirely.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm uses a ''sources and uses'' table to plan an LBO. What does this table show?', '["The company''s historical revenue sources","Where the deal''s funding comes from (equity, senior debt, junior debt, rollover equity) and how it is applied (purchase price, refinanced debt, transaction fees, cash to balance sheet)","The company''s operating expenses","The fund''s LP commitments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The sources and uses table is the fundamental summary of an LBO''s funding structure. Sources list every form of capital: PE sponsor equity, senior debt, junior debt/unitranche, rollover equity, and any cash available. Uses list every application: enterprise value paid for the target, refinancing of existing debt, transaction fees, and initial cash on the balance sheet. Sources must equal uses — they are the two sides of the same equation.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm structures its LBO to include €8M of transaction fees (legal, advisory, due diligence, debt arrangement). How are these typically funded?', '["They are waived by advisers in PE transactions","They are funded at closing through the same ''sources'' (debt and equity) that fund the purchase price, essentially added to the overall deal cost","They are paid by the seller","They are deferred and paid from future operating profits"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Transaction fees (typically 2-4% of enterprise value) are funded at closing through the same mix of debt and equity that funds the purchase price. They increase the total deal size and either the equity check or debt quantum. Debt arrangement fees are often capitalised (added to the loan balance). Legal and advisory fees are typically paid in cash at closing. These fees represent a real cost that must be recovered through exit value.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'An LBO financing package includes a ''revolving credit facility'' (RCF) of €25M. What is this facility used for?', '["To fund the initial acquisition of the target","To provide ongoing working capital funding and operational flexibility during the hold period, allowing the company to draw and repay as cash flow fluctuates","To refinance the PE fund''s investments","To pay dividends to the PE fund"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The revolving credit facility (RCF) provides flexible working capital funding during the hold period. Unlike term loans that fund the acquisition itself, the RCF is available to draw and repay as cash flow fluctuates — funding seasonal working capital, bridging timing differences, or supporting small acquisitions. RCF availability provides operational safety margin and is typically undrawn at closing (€25M available but €0 drawn).'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm considers whether to include debt ''covenants'' in an LBO financing. What are covenants and how do they affect the deal?', '["Covenants are marketing arrangements between the PE firm and the lender","Covenants are contractual requirements the borrower must maintain (financial ratios, operational thresholds); breach gives lenders intervention rights, providing lenders early warning of distress","Covenants are tax agreements","Covenants have no practical effect"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Covenants are contractual requirements in debt agreements: financial covenants (maintain leverage below 7.0x, interest coverage above 2.0x), negative covenants (no dividends without permission, no sale of key assets, limits on additional debt), and affirmative covenants (provide regular financial reporting, maintain insurance). Breach does not automatically trigger default — it gives lenders intervention rights and negotiation leverage, enabling early course correction.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm''s LBO financing includes ''covenant-lite'' debt. What does this term mean?', '["Debt with no repayment obligations","Debt with minimal maintenance covenants, meaning lenders cannot intervene based on financial ratio deterioration unless a specific triggering event occurs","Debt at below-market interest rates","Debt with no interest payments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Covenant-lite debt minimises or eliminates maintenance financial covenants (leverage ratios tested periodically). Instead, covenants only apply on specific actions (additional debt, dividends, acquisitions). This gives borrowers more operational flexibility and protects against covenant-driven restructuring during temporary performance weakness. From the lender''s perspective, it reduces early intervention rights. Cov-lite structures became dominant in the 2010s driven by competitive lender markets.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm''s deal team presents an investment to the IC at a 10x entry multiple. The IC pushes back, asking to see a ''football field'' analysis. What does this analysis show?', '["The company''s revenue from sports-related sectors","A visual display of valuation ranges across multiple methodologies (trading comps, deal comps, DCF, LBO) allowing comparison of results and identification of a convergence zone","The company''s organisational chart","The deal team''s hourly rates"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A football field shows the valuation ranges produced by each method side-by-side: trading multiples at €450-550M, deal multiples at €480-580M, DCF at €440-530M, and LBO ability-to-pay at €500-540M. Overlap between methods identifies a defensible pricing range; gaps suggest methodological issues. The IC uses this visualisation to pressure-test whether the proposed entry price is supported by independent reference points.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm commits to an acquisition subject to ''financing certainty.'' What does this mean and why does it matter to the seller?', '["The PE firm guarantees its own profits","The PE firm has binding debt commitments from lenders that ensure the transaction can close without financing risk, giving the seller confidence the deal will actually complete","The PE firm agrees to use all-equity funding","The PE firm insures the transaction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Financing certainty means the PE firm has binding debt commitment letters from lenders — not just indicative proposals. This matters to the seller because the deal will not collapse due to debt market volatility between signing and closing. In competitive auctions, financing certainty is a differentiator: bids without committed financing are discounted regardless of headline price. Lenders charge fees for the committed backstop, which PE firms build into the transaction economics.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'deal-concepts', 'A PE firm acquires a company using a ''bidco'' (bidding company) structure — a newly created entity that makes the acquisition. Why is this structure standard in LBOs?', '["It allows the PE firm to avoid regulatory oversight","It isolates the acquisition from the PE fund''s other investments, houses the acquisition debt, and provides a clean legal vehicle for subsequent actions (bolt-ons, refinancing, exit)","It reduces the taxes on the deal","It is required by international law"]'::jsonb, 1, 'BidCo (often stacked with HoldCo and other vehicles) isolates each PE investment in its own legal structure. The BidCo holds the acquisition debt, making the debt specific to that deal and not cross-contaminating other portfolio companies. It provides a clean vehicle for management equity programmes, bolt-on acquisitions, and eventual exit. The acquisition structure also has tax implications that drive jurisdiction and structure decisions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A $2 billion PE fund closes in January 2023. Two years later, the GP has called approximately $1.2 billion to fund six platform acquisitions. An LP asks when they will receive distributions. What is the most accurate answer based on typical fund dynamics?', '["Distributions begin immediately after each capital call as investments generate cash flow","Distributions typically begin 3–5 years into the fund life as portfolio companies are exited","Distributions are paid annually based on portfolio company EBITDA growth","Distributions only occur at fund termination in year 10"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE funds follow a J-curve pattern. Years 1-3 involve capital deployment with minimal distributions. Distributions typically accelerate in years 4-8 as portfolio companies are exited. This J-curve is inherent to PE and is why short-term performance measurement is misleading for the asset class.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A GP raises a $1 billion fund with standard 2-and-20 terms and an 8% hurdle. After 10 years, the fund returns $2.2 billion to investors. Under a standard European (whole-fund) waterfall, approximately how much does the GP receive as carried interest?', '["$200 million — 20% of the gross fund return","$100 million — 10% of the net profit","$175 million — 20% of profits above the preferred return","$440 million — 20% of the total distribution"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Under a European waterfall: LPs receive capital back ($1.0B) plus 8% preferred return. Profits above the hurdle are then subject to 20% carry. Approximate carry: roughly $175-180M. Carry is calculated on profits above the hurdle, not on gross distributions or the whole fund return.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE firm''s GP and LPs have negotiated a clawback provision in the LPA. In which scenario would this provision be triggered?', '["The GP outperforms the hurdle rate and LPs want to reduce the GP''s carry percentage","The fund generates strong early exits but later investments underperform, leaving the GP with excess carry already distributed","A key senior partner departs the firm during the investment period","The fund life is extended beyond the original 10-year term"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Clawback provisions protect LPs when strong early exits cause the GP to receive carry, but subsequent underperformance means the GP was over-distributed relative to the fund''s final overall return. The GP must return the excess carry to LPs. Key-person events and fund extensions trigger different provisions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A pension fund is evaluating a commitment to a new PE fund. The GP proposes a 2% management fee on committed capital during the investment period, dropping to 1.5% on invested capital thereafter. What is the economic significance of this step-down?', '["It is a loophole that allows the GP to extract additional fees after deployment","It aligns fees with the GP''s actual workload — active investing versus portfolio management","It increases LP costs over time as the fund matures","It is required by regulators in most jurisdictions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The step-down reflects the economic reality that active deal-making during the investment period requires more resources than portfolio management during the harvest period. It also reduces fee drag on LP returns once the fund is fully deployed. The step-down is a market convention, not a regulatory requirement.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'The Limited Partnership Agreement (LPA) is the foundational legal document governing a PE fund. What does it primarily establish?', '["Only the management fee rate","The full framework of the fund: term, economics (fees and carry), governance rights, investment restrictions, LP-GP relationship, and dispute resolution","The portfolio companies the fund will acquire","The identity of the LPs"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The LPA is a comprehensive document (often 100-200+ pages) establishing every economic and governance term of the fund: fund term, investment period, management fee, carry waterfall, GP commit, key-person provisions, LPAC authority, investment restrictions, excuse rights, and default remedies. LPs and their counsel negotiate heavily on LPA terms before committing.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund has received $500M in committed capital. An LP that committed $25M asks why her bank account has not been debited for the full amount. What explains this?', '["The LP has failed to transfer her commitment","PE fund commitments are ''called'' gradually over the investment period as investments are made, not transferred upfront","The fund is not yet operational","The LP will receive her capital back annually"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE funds do not hold LP capital upfront. LPs sign commitment agreements for a specified amount, and the GP ''calls'' portions of that commitment (typically with 10-15 business days'' notice) as investments are made over the investment period — usually 4-6 years. This structure is efficient for LPs (capital earns returns elsewhere until needed) but creates the ''dry powder'' phenomenon for the GP.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A typical closed-end PE fund has a ''term'' of 10 years with possible extensions. What does this term structure mean for LPs?', '["LPs can withdraw capital at any point during the 10 years","Capital is effectively locked up for the full fund life — LPs cannot request return of capital before exits occur, and the GP has ~10 years to complete the investment cycle and return capital","The fund pays guaranteed returns for 10 years","LPs must reinvest returns in the fund for 10 years"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Closed-end PE funds have defined terms (typically 10 years with 1-2 year extension options). During this period, LP capital cannot be withdrawn — distributions come only from realised investments. The GP has the full term to acquire, improve, and exit portfolio companies, then wind down. This structural illiquidity is fundamental to the PE model and is why LPs require return premiums.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund''s LPA divides the fund life into an ''investment period'' and a ''harvest period.'' What distinguishes these phases?', '["The investment period is shorter than the harvest period because deployment is faster than exits","Investment period (typically first 4-6 years) is when new platform acquisitions are made; harvest period focuses on value creation in existing portfolio and exits, with new investments typically restricted","Both periods are identical in activity and purpose","The harvest period comes first in the fund life"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The investment period (4-6 years) is when the GP deploys capital into new platform investments. After the investment period ends, the fund enters the harvest period: the GP manages the existing portfolio, pursues follow-on investments and bolt-ons, and executes exits. New platform acquisitions are typically not permitted during the harvest period, though follow-ons and bolt-ons to existing investments are allowed.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'An LP evaluating a new fund describes it as ''vintage 2024.'' What does vintage year refer to, and why does it matter?', '["The year the fund was conceived by the GP","The year the fund held its final close and began making investments; it matters because market conditions at vintage affect entry pricing, leverage availability, and ultimately returns","The LP''s birth year","The date the fund must be fully exited"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Vintage year marks when the fund began deploying capital. It matters because macro conditions (credit availability, valuation multiples, competition for deals, subsequent economic cycles) at the time of deployment shape fund returns. Vintages deploying into boom periods often underperform; vintages deploying into troughs (2002, 2009) often outperform. LPs use vintage-year benchmarks to compare funds in equivalent market conditions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A fund is approaching the end of its 10-year term with three portfolio companies unsold. The GP requests a 2-year extension from LPs. What is the typical purpose of such an extension?', '["To extract additional management fees","To provide time to execute orderly exits rather than selling into weak markets at discounted prices","To add new platform investments","To change the fund''s strategy"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Extensions (typically 1-2 years, sometimes 3) provide time to execute orderly exits rather than fire-selling assets into unfavourable markets. Extensions typically require LPAC or LP majority approval. Management fees during extensions are typically reduced or eliminated to avoid creating perverse incentives for the GP to prolong the fund. Extensions are increasingly common due to longer hold periods and weaker exit markets.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'The ''2-and-20'' fee structure is the traditional PE fund economic model. What do the ''2'' and ''20'' refer to?', '["2% of invested capital as fees, 20% of the fund''s deals","2% annual management fee on committed capital, 20% carried interest on profits above the hurdle","2 partners per deal, 20% staffing overhead","2 years of lock-up, 20% early redemption penalty"]'::jsonb, 1, '2-and-20 refers to the two components of GP compensation: 2% annual management fee (on committed capital during the investment period, often dropping to ~1.5% on invested capital in the harvest period) and 20% carried interest on profits above the preferred return hurdle. Top-tier firms sometimes charge higher (2.5% or 30% carry), while newer or emerging managers may offer discounts.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund has $1.5B in committed capital but has only invested $900M in portfolio companies. During the investment period, what is the management fee paid by LPs?', '["2% of $900M = $18M annually","2% of $1.5B = $30M annually (on committed capital)","2% of $600M unused capital = $12M annually","Fees are suspended until the fund is fully invested"]'::jsonb, 1, 'During the investment period, management fees are typically charged on committed capital ($1.5B), not invested capital ($900M). This generates $30M annually regardless of deployment pace. After the investment period, the fee base typically drops to invested capital and the rate steps down (e.g., from 2% to 1.5%), reducing both the fee basis and rate.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE portfolio company pays the GP''s sponsor a ''monitoring fee'' of $2M annually for services during the hold period. How is this typically treated under modern LPA terms?', '["It is an additional fee that increases total GP compensation beyond the management fee","It typically offsets the management fee to LPs (100% offset is now standard), so LPs effectively keep the economic benefit","It is paid directly to LPs","It is not permitted under any LPA"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Monitoring fees, transaction fees, and other fees received by the GP from portfolio companies historically flowed straight to the GP. Modern LPA standards require 100% offset against the management fee, meaning LPs effectively capture these fees. This structural change, led by sophisticated LPs over the past 15 years, eliminates a source of fee leakage that existed in earlier PE vintages.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A GP pays $3M in legal fees, placement agent fees, and regulatory setup costs when establishing a new $2B fund. How are these ''organisational expenses'' typically treated?', '["The GP pays them entirely from its own resources","They are typically capped (often at $1-2M) and reimbursed to the GP from fund capital, with any excess paid by the GP personally","LPs pay them directly separate from their commitments","They are amortised across portfolio company budgets"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Organisational expenses (legal, placement, regulatory, marketing) are typically capped in the LPA (often $1-2M for mid-market funds; higher for mega-funds). Up to the cap, the fund reimburses the GP; any excess is paid by the GP personally. LPs monitor these caps carefully because uncapped organisational expenses can be a source of fee creep. Placement agent fees beyond the cap are often specifically excluded.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'What is the fundamental purpose of carried interest in PE fund economics?', '["To guarantee the GP a minimum return","To align GP compensation with fund performance — the GP only earns meaningful compensation if LPs earn strong returns","To cover fund operational expenses","To compensate LPs for their time"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Carried interest is the economic mechanism that aligns GP and LP interests. Management fees provide baseline income, but carry (typically 20% of profits above hurdle) can dwarf management fees in successful funds. This back-loaded compensation structure incentivises the GP to maximise long-term fund returns rather than asset accumulation. Carry only pays after LPs receive their capital back plus the preferred return.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund has an 8% preferred return (hurdle rate). What does this mean for the GP''s ability to earn carry?', '["The GP earns carry only on returns above 8%","LPs must receive their invested capital back plus an 8% annualised return before the GP earns any carried interest (subject to catch-up if applicable)","The GP guarantees LPs an 8% return","LPs receive only 8% of fund returns"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The preferred return (hurdle) is the minimum return LPs must receive before GP carry begins. Typical 8% preferred: LPs receive 100% of distributions until they have capital back plus 8% annualised return; then (if catch-up applies) GP receives 100% of subsequent distributions until catch-up is satisfied; then GP receives 20% of remaining profits. The hurdle protects LPs from paying carry on mediocre performance.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'After LPs receive their preferred return, many PE funds include a ''catch-up'' provision. How does this typically work?', '["The GP receives 100% of distributions until it has caught up to a specified share of profits (often 20%), then 20-80 carry split resumes","LPs receive additional distributions to catch up to the GP","The fund extends by 1 year to catch up on investments","The GP personally invests more capital"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A 100% catch-up (standard in many funds) means: after LPs receive preferred return, the GP receives 100% of subsequent distributions until it has caught up to 20% of total profits distributed. Then future distributions follow the 80-20 split. This makes the overall waterfall arrive at a 20% carry economically — the GP earns 20% of all profits above hurdle, just with a compressed payment pattern. Some funds use 50% or 80% catch-up, which lowers effective GP economics.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund uses an ''American'' waterfall rather than a ''European'' waterfall. What is the key difference for the timing of GP carry distributions?', '["There is no practical difference between the two","American (deal-by-deal) waterfall calculates carry on each exit; European (whole-fund) waterfall calculates carry only after total capital is returned plus preferred return","American waterfalls charge higher fees","European waterfalls only apply to European LPs"]'::jsonb, 1, 'American waterfall (deal-by-deal): GP earns carry on each successful exit, as long as that deal cleared the hurdle. European waterfall (whole-fund): GP earns no carry until total fund capital plus preferred return has been distributed to LPs. European is more LP-friendly (GP bears risk that underperforming later deals erode carry from strong early deals); American is GP-friendlier (carry flows earlier). Clawback provisions are especially important in American structures.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund''s LPA specifies that senior partners receive 60% of carry, mid-level principals 25%, and vice presidents 10%, with 5% allocated to an operating partner pool. What does this allocation reflect?', '["A fixed legal requirement","The internal economic hierarchy of the GP firm, reflecting seniority, track record, and contribution; specific allocations are highly variable and often a source of internal tension","The LPs'' preferred distribution","An industry-standard allocation that never varies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Carry allocation among partners is a private economic matter within the GP firm, not disclosed to LPs. Typical patterns: founder/senior partners receive 40-60%, mid-level partners 20-30%, junior professionals 5-10%, and operating/functional professionals a dedicated pool. Allocation shifts across vintages as new partners earn larger shares. Internal disputes over carry allocation are a major source of partner departures and have destroyed multiple PE firms.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A $3B PE fund requires the GP to invest 2% of committed capital personally — the GP commit. What amount must the GP contribute, and why is this structurally important?', '["$30M; it ensures the GP has meaningful personal capital at risk alongside LPs","$60M; it demonstrates GP confidence and aligns incentives with LPs through shared risk","$6M; it covers fund operational costs","No GP commit is typically required"]'::jsonb, 1, 'At 2% of $3B, the GP commits $60M personally. This commitment (typically 1-5% of fund size, increasingly pushed higher by LPs) ensures the GP has meaningful personal capital at risk on every deal. When deals lose money, the GP loses its own capital — creating structural alignment that management fees alone cannot achieve. Top-tier firms increasingly commit 3-5%+ to demonstrate confidence in competitive fundraising.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund issues a ''capital call'' to its LPs. What is this, and how quickly must LPs respond?', '["A demand for LPs to increase their total commitments","A formal notice requesting LPs to transfer a portion of their committed capital (typically for a specific investment), due within 10-15 business days","A quarterly performance update","A vote on fund decisions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Capital calls are formal drawdown notices from the GP to LPs requesting transfer of a specified amount of committed capital, typically due within 10-15 business days. Calls fund specific investments, management fees, or expenses. LPs that fail to fund (LP default) face severe consequences: forfeiture of existing investment, interest charges, and potential exclusion from future funds. Planned calls are often communicated in advance to help LPs manage liquidity.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'An industry commentator notes that global PE ''dry powder'' is at $3.7 trillion. What does dry powder refer to?', '["Cash held on portfolio company balance sheets","Committed LP capital that has not yet been called and deployed into investments","Reserves held by the GP firm itself","The total value of portfolio companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Dry powder is the industry term for committed-but-undeployed LP capital. A fund with $2B committed and $700M deployed has $1.3B of dry powder available for investment. High industry-wide dry powder creates competitive pressure for deployment (chasing limited attractive deals, driving multiples up) while signalling LP confidence in PE as an asset class. Dry powder levels correlate with entry multiples.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund reserves 20-30% of committed capital for ''follow-on investments'' rather than deploying it into new platform acquisitions. Why?', '["To reduce the GP''s management fee base","To fund bolt-on acquisitions, additional equity injections, or opportunistic investments in existing portfolio companies during the hold period","To return capital to LPs early","To pay operational expenses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Reserve capital (20-30% of fund size) is held back to fund follow-on needs: bolt-on acquisitions for platform companies, additional equity for growth or distressed situations, equity cure payments to resolve covenant breaches, or opportunistic add-ons. A fund that deploys 100% into platform deals has no flexibility for follow-ons, which forces either reliance on co-investment or missed opportunities in the existing portfolio.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A fund''s LPA includes ''recycling provisions.'' What do these allow the GP to do?', '["Resell the same portfolio company multiple times","Redeploy capital returned from short-hold exits (or fees received) back into new investments, effectively allowing greater total deployment than committed capital","Replace LPs that default on capital calls","Convert carry into management fees"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Recycling provisions allow the GP to reinvest capital returned from early exits (typically within the first 2-3 years) or from transaction fees. A $1B fund with recycling might effectively deploy $1.1-1.2B over its life. Recycling benefits the fund by extending deployment capacity without additional LP commitments. LPs typically cap recycling (e.g., maximum 20-25% above committed capital) and restrict it to early exits.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A GP uses a ''subscription line'' or ''capital call facility'' — a revolving credit line secured by LP commitments — to fund initial investments. What is the effect on reported fund returns?', '["No effect on returns","It delays capital calls from LPs, boosting reported IRR by shortening the period LP capital is deployed, though MOIC is unaffected","It reduces total distributions to LPs","It is prohibited by most LPAs"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subscription lines allow GPs to fund investments with short-term borrowing rather than immediate LP capital calls. This delays when LP capital clock starts running, mathematically inflating IRR (the return period shrinks). MOIC is unaffected. LPs are increasingly scrutinising this practice; some require reporting of ''pre-sub-line'' IRR. Subscription lines are useful for cash management but can be misleading when used for IRR enhancement.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund exits a portfolio company for €200M in cash. How are these proceeds typically distributed to LPs?', '["Immediately in full to LPs","Distributed according to the fund''s waterfall (return of capital, preferred return, catch-up, carry split) typically within 30-60 days of closing","Held in the fund until term end","Reinvested in new deals automatically"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Exit proceeds flow through the fund''s waterfall in sequence: (1) return of capital invested in that deal (or the fund, under European waterfall); (2) preferred return to LPs; (3) GP catch-up (if applicable); (4) 80-20 split of remaining profits. Cash distributions to LPs typically occur within 30-60 days of exit closing, often as ''distribution notices'' specifying source deal, amount, and classification (capital, preferred return, profit).'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A fund''s LPA requires LPAC approval for ''conflict transactions.'' Which of the following would typically require LPAC consent?', '["Routine bolt-on acquisitions","Transactions between the fund and another vehicle managed by the same GP (cross-fund investments, affiliated party transactions), valuation methodology changes, and certain GP-favourable decisions","Any investment above $100M","All investment decisions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LPAC approval is typically required for transactions with inherent conflicts: cross-fund investments (Fund III buying from Fund II), affiliated party transactions (GP''s captive credit fund lending to a buyout portfolio company), valuation methodology changes, fund life extensions, and certain GP indemnification matters. LPAC approval does not cover routine investment decisions — those remain GP discretion.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund''s LPA includes ''key-person provisions.'' What do these typically do?', '["Grant the key persons veto rights over LP decisions","Suspend the investment period or trigger LP rights if specified senior partners (the ''key persons'') cease to be actively involved in the fund","Require key persons to invest personal capital","Mandate succession planning"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Key-person provisions specify senior individuals essential to the fund''s strategy. If a specified number of key persons cease to be actively devoted to the fund (death, disability, departure, reduced time commitment), the investment period is automatically suspended until LPs decide how to proceed (resume with new key persons, terminate early, or restructure). This protects LPs from paying fees and deploying capital when the team they backed is no longer in place.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A fund LPA includes a ''no-fault divorce'' provision. What rights does this provide LPs?', '["The right to sue the GP for any reason","The right (typically requiring a supermajority of LP votes, e.g., 75%) to terminate the fund or remove the GP without proving cause","The right to withdraw capital at any time","The right to force the GP to divorce a partner"]'::jsonb, 1, 'No-fault divorce provisions allow LPs — typically by a high threshold like 75% supermajority — to terminate the investment period or remove the GP without proving wrongdoing. This is a significant LP protection but rarely exercised because the vote threshold is high. For-cause termination (proven misconduct, conviction, or specified breaches) has lower thresholds but requires evidence. These provisions are standard in modern LPAs.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'When a PE firm raises its third fund, it often raises significantly more capital than its first or second funds. Why does fund size typically grow across vintages?', '["Regulatory requirements force size increases","Successful track record, expanded LP relationships, and ability to execute larger deals enable larger subsequent fundraises","Fund sizes are fixed by law","Fund sizes decrease with experience"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE fund sizes typically grow across vintages for several reasons: successful track record attracts more LPs and larger commitments; existing LPs increase allocations; GP builds capacity to deploy more capital; firm may target larger deals as it grows. However, size growth is not automatic — poor prior performance can prevent growth or force downsize. Some LPs specifically resist excessive fund size growth (concerns about strategy drift or reduced attention per deal).'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE firm simultaneously raises Fund IV (new capital) while still managing Fund III (existing investments). What structural concern does this create and how is it typically managed?', '["No concerns — this is standard practice with no implications","Conflict over new investment allocation between funds; typically managed through LPA restrictions (Fund III cannot invest once Fund IV is operational, with specified exceptions for follow-ons)","It is legally prohibited","Fund IV must return all capital to Fund III LPs first"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Overlapping fund periods create allocation conflicts: which fund gets a new deal? LPAs typically address this with ''successor fund'' provisions. Fund III''s investment period ends when Fund IV hits a specified funding threshold (often 75% or final close). After that, new platform investments go to Fund IV; Fund III can only pursue follow-ons to existing deals. Transition rules and allocation policies are heavily negotiated and LPAC-monitored.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A US-based PE firm raises a fund with both ''onshore'' (US investors) and ''offshore'' (non-US investors) parallel vehicles. What is the purpose of this structure?', '["To confuse LPs","To address different tax and regulatory needs of US versus non-US investors while investing side-by-side in the same deals","To deploy capital in different geographies","To charge different fees"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Parallel fund structures accommodate different tax and regulatory frameworks: US investors typically invest through a Delaware LP, non-US investors through a Cayman Islands or Luxembourg vehicle, tax-exempt investors through a blocker corporation. All parallel vehicles invest side-by-side in the same deals, pro-rata. This structure is standard for funds raising from international LPs and is invisible to the underlying investments.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A fund structures a ''feeder'' vehicle for high-net-worth individuals, aggregating many smaller commitments into a single position in the main fund. What purpose does this serve?', '["To charge HNW investors higher fees","To allow smaller HNW commitments (e.g., €250K-€5M each) to access institutional fund minimums (€5M+), while the GP manages a single LP relationship rather than hundreds","To exclude HNW investors from the fund","To avoid regulatory requirements"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Feeder vehicles pool smaller HNW commitments (aggregated by private banks, multi-family offices, or the GP''s own feeder) into a single LP position in the main fund. Advantages: HNW investors access the fund below its standard minimum; the GP manages one LP relationship rather than hundreds; operational simplicity. Feeders typically charge additional fees on top of the underlying fund, which HNW investors pay for access.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'Most traditional PE funds are ''closed-end'' structures. What distinguishes these from ''open-ended'' (evergreen) fund structures?', '["Open-ended funds are much larger","Closed-end: defined term (10 years), committed capital, no new subscriptions after final close, illiquid. Open-ended: indefinite life, rolling subscriptions and redemptions (subject to caps)","No difference — these terms are interchangeable","Closed-end funds invest only in closed companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Closed-end funds have defined terms, committed capital structures, one-time fundraising, and no redemptions — the dominant PE structure. Open-ended (evergreen) funds have indefinite life, rolling subscriptions, periodic redemptions (subject to liquidity caps), and continuous NAV calculations. Evergreens are increasingly common in democratisation products (BDCs, interval funds) and offer LPs optional liquidity at the cost of some return optimisation.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A first-time fund manager is raising $300M, significantly smaller than established firms'' funds. What challenges do first-time managers typically face?', '["Regulatory exemptions that prevent fundraising","Limited track record to demonstrate skill, difficulty accessing institutional LPs that avoid first-time funds, and need to offer more LP-friendly terms to build a base","Excessive demand from LPs","Minimum fund sizes set by regulators"]'::jsonb, 1, 'First-time managers face significant challenges: no fund-level track record (though partners may have attributable deal history), limited institutional LP access (many institutions avoid first-time funds categorically), longer fundraising timelines (often 18-24 months), and pressure to offer concessions (lower fees, better reporting, larger GP commit). First-time funds typically depend heavily on HNW, family office, and fund-of-funds LPs. Strong first funds position GPs for mainstream institutional access in Fund II-III.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'An LP evaluating a PE fund asks about the ''target return.'' What does a typical mid-market buyout fund target?', '["5-10% net IRR, similar to public equity","20-25% gross IRR, translating to approximately 15-18% net IRR after fees and carry","50%+ net IRR","Below inflation"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mid-market buyout funds typically target 20-25% gross IRR at the deal level, translating to 15-18% net IRR to LPs after management fees and carry. MOIC targets are typically 2.0-2.5x gross per deal. These returns reflect the illiquidity premium over public markets. Growth equity funds may target slightly lower returns; venture capital aims higher (30%+) to compensate for much higher loss rates. Actual returns vary enormously by vintage and manager.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A $2B fund with a 5-year investment period would typically deploy capital at what approximate pace?', '["All $2B in the first 6 months","Roughly $300-500M per year on 2-4 platform investments, spread across the investment period to manage vintage year risk and maintain underwriting discipline","$100M per year, completing deployment in year 20","Deployment pace is random"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A disciplined $2B fund deploys roughly $300-500M annually over the 5-year investment period, completing 8-15 platform investments total. This pace allows diversification across vintage conditions, maintains underwriting discipline, and preserves capacity for follow-ons. Faster deployment (''deployment pressure'') is a warning sign — it often correlates with overpaying, reduced diligence depth, or selecting weaker opportunities to hit deployment targets.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund''s performance can be measured using ''gross'' returns (at the deal level) or ''net'' returns (to LPs after fees and carry). Why does this distinction matter to LP evaluation?', '["Gross and net returns are always identical","Gross returns measure investment selection and operational value creation; net returns reflect what LPs actually earn after fee drag — typically 3-7 percentage points lower","Only gross returns matter","Net returns measure fund size"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Gross returns measure pure investment performance (what the deals earned before fund economics). Net returns measure what LPs actually received after management fees and carry. The gap between gross and net — the ''fee drag'' — is typically 3-7 percentage points for well-performing funds. LPs care about net returns (their actual economics); GPs tend to emphasise gross returns (their operational achievement). Sophisticated LPs analyse both.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'An LP wants to redeem her commitment in a closed-end PE fund. What options does she have?', '["Submit a redemption request to the GP for immediate payment","Sell her LP interest on the secondary market to another investor at a negotiated price (often at a discount to NAV), subject to GP consent and transfer restrictions","Withdraw her capital at any time","LPs have no ability to exit before fund term"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LPs cannot demand redemption from a closed-end PE fund. The only liquidity option is the secondary market: selling the LP interest to another institutional investor (typically a secondary fund like Ardian, Lexington, or Partners Group Secondaries). Transactions are at negotiated prices (historically at NAV discounts, though recent premiums have occurred for top funds) and require GP consent plus compliance with LPA transfer restrictions. Secondaries are now a ~$100B+ annual market.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'fund-structure', 'A PE fund distributes €150M to LPs from a recent portfolio company exit. The accompanying notice classifies €100M as ''return of capital'' and €50M as ''profit.'' Why does this classification matter?', '["It has no practical significance","The classification determines waterfall treatment (capital returned fills the LP return-of-capital bucket; profit may be subject to preferred return, catch-up, and carry) and affects tax treatment in the LP''s hands","It determines whether the distribution is cash or in-kind","It specifies which LP receives the distribution"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Distribution classification is economically significant. Return of capital reduces the LP''s unreturned capital (progress toward hurdle calculation); profit is subject to the fund''s waterfall (preferred return, catch-up, carry split). Tax treatment also varies: return of capital is not immediately taxable in most jurisdictions; profit distributions are typically subject to capital gains tax. LPs track distribution components carefully in their portfolio accounting.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE fund''s Limited Partnership Agreement specifies that LPs contribute 98% of the fund''s capital. Yet the General Partner makes every investment decision without LP approval. What structural principle explains why LPs accept this arrangement?', '["LPs retain veto rights through the investment committee","LPs are paid a higher return than the GP to compensate for their passive role","Limited partnership structure trades LP control for limited liability and professional management","LPs can withdraw their capital at any time if they disagree with investment decisions"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The limited partnership structure grants LPs limited liability (capped at their commitment) and access to professional management in exchange for passivity in investment decisions. LPs cannot withdraw committed capital on demand, have no veto over individual investments, and do not earn higher returns than the GP — they earn different economics structured through the waterfall.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A mid-market PE firm is considering hiring its first operating partner. Which statement best captures the function this role typically performs?', '["Sources new investment opportunities through industry networks and warm introductions","Provides operational expertise across portfolio companies — interim leadership, functional improvement, or sector guidance","Manages the fund''s regulatory filings, compliance obligations, and LP reporting requirements","Negotiates debt financing terms with lenders on behalf of the deal team"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Operating partners are typically former CEOs, CFOs, or functional experts who work directly with portfolio companies — serving as interim executives, leading operational improvement projects, or providing sector-specific expertise during diligence and ownership. Deal sourcing, compliance, and financing are performed by other roles within the firm.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'CLO managers have become one of the most important participants in the PE ecosystem, yet they rarely appear in news coverage of individual deals. What role do they play?', '["They provide equity co-investment alongside PE funds in large buyouts","They are the single largest buyer of leveraged loans issued to finance LBOs","They advise portfolio companies on operational improvements during the hold period","They conduct independent valuations of PE fund portfolios for LP reporting purposes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Collateralised Loan Obligation (CLO) managers pool leveraged loans into structured vehicles and issue tranched securities to investors. They are the largest institutional buyer of the loans that finance PE-backed LBOs — making them a critical, if invisible, component of the PE debt ecosystem.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm is evaluating a proprietary deal opportunity — a founder-owned industrial business that was introduced through the firm''s operating partner network. What competitive advantage does this sourcing channel typically provide?', '["Lower regulatory scrutiny because the deal bypasses investment bank involvement","Guaranteed approval from the investment committee since senior partners made the introduction","Less competition and often better pricing than a formal auction process","Reduced legal costs because founder-owned businesses require no SPA documentation"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Proprietary deal flow — where the PE firm is the primary or only bidder — typically produces better pricing and less competitive tension than formal auctions run by investment banks. This is why firms invest heavily in building industry relationships. Regulatory requirements, IC approval standards, and legal documentation do not change based on sourcing channel.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm''s investment committee reviews every proposed acquisition before the deal team can sign. What is the primary purpose of this governance layer?', '["To comply with SEC requirements for PE firms","To provide independent challenge to the deal team''s analysis and prevent deal bias from driving poor decisions","To allow LPs to approve or reject individual transactions","To negotiate the final purchase price with the seller"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The investment committee exists to provide independent, experienced challenge to the deal team. Teams that have spent months on a transaction develop commitment bias and can miss risks. The IC typically includes senior partners not involved in the deal. This institutional discipline is central to why well-governed PE firms avoid costly mistakes.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A senior partner at a PE firm typically sits on the board of 3-5 portfolio companies simultaneously. Why is this structural requirement important to the PE model?', '["Regulatory rules require PE partners to hold board seats","Board presence is how PE firms exercise the active ownership and governance that distinguishes their model from passive investing","Partners earn additional fees for each board seat they hold","Board positions provide tax advantages for the individual partner"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Board participation is the operational mechanism through which PE firms exercise control and drive value creation. Partners use board meetings to challenge strategy, approve major decisions, track KPIs, and ensure the 100-day plan stays on course. This active governance is a defining feature of PE ownership, distinct from passive public equity investing.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'An analyst at a PE firm spends most of their time on financial modelling, market research, and data room analysis. What is the typical progression from analyst to partner, and approximately how long does it take?', '["Analyst → Associate → VP → Principal → Partner, typically 10-15 years with strong performance","Analyst → Partner directly within 2-3 years","Analyst positions do not lead to partner roles; partners are always recruited from investment banks","The progression is immediate upon MBA graduation"]'::jsonb, 0, 'PE firms typically have a multi-stage progression: Analyst (2-3 years, often post-banking), Associate (2-3 years), VP (2-3 years), Principal/Director (2-4 years), then Partner. Total timeline to partner is typically 10-15 years with strong performance, though some firms compress this and others skip levels. MBAs often enter at Associate level.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE partner''s compensation structure includes base salary, annual bonus, and carried interest. Which component typically represents the largest share of a senior partner''s lifetime earnings in a successful fund?', '["Base salary, because it is guaranteed and accumulates over decades","Annual bonus, because it is tied to fund performance year-by-year","Carried interest, because successful funds can generate returns that produce carry payments many multiples of the partner''s salary","Management fees paid directly to individual partners"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Carried interest — the 20% share of fund profits above the hurdle — is the defining economic driver for senior PE professionals. A strong senior partner''s carry from a single successful fund can exceed several years of combined salary and bonus. This is why PE compensation is heavily back-loaded and aligned with long-term fund performance.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE fund''s LPA requires the GP to invest 2% of the fund''s committed capital personally — the ''GP commit.'' Why is this requirement structurally important to LPs?', '["It provides additional capital to the fund for deal-making","It ensures the GP has meaningful personal capital at risk alongside LP capital, aligning incentives","It demonstrates the GP''s regulatory compliance","It reduces the fund''s overall expense ratio"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The GP commitment (typically 1-5% of fund size) ensures the GP has genuine personal capital at risk in every deal. This alignment is one of PE''s strongest structural features: when things go wrong, the GP loses money alongside LPs, creating incentives against taking excessive risk purely to earn carry. LPs increasingly demand higher GP commits in competitive fundraising environments.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Most PE firms are organised as limited partnerships or limited liability partnerships rather than corporations. Why is this legal structure preferred?', '["It reduces the firm''s tax burden significantly","It passes profits directly to partners without corporate-level taxation and provides flexibility in profit allocation","It protects the firm from regulatory oversight","It allows the firm to avoid registering with securities regulators"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Partnership structures are tax pass-through entities: profits (and losses) flow directly to partners without being taxed at the firm level. This is crucial for PE economics, where individual partners receive carry allocations that would be double-taxed in a corporate structure. Partnerships also provide flexibility in how profits are divided among partners.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm describes itself as a ''sector specialist'' focused exclusively on healthcare services. How does this positioning typically differ from a generalist firm''s approach?', '["Specialist firms have fewer regulatory obligations than generalists","Specialists develop deep industry knowledge, proprietary deal flow, and operational playbooks within their sector, but sacrifice the diversification of a multi-sector portfolio","Specialists only hire industry executives, not finance professionals","Specialists avoid using leverage in their transactions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sector specialists (like Thoma Bravo in software, Welsh Carson in healthcare) develop deep industry expertise: understanding regulatory dynamics, competitive structures, management networks, and operational playbooks within their vertical. This concentration produces sourcing advantages and execution capabilities that generalists struggle to match, at the cost of sector concentration risk.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Across the global PE industry, which LP category contributes the largest share of total committed capital?', '["Individual retail investors","Public and private pension funds","Hedge funds","Commercial banks"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Public and private pension funds are collectively the largest LP category, contributing roughly 30-40% of global PE capital. Major examples include CalPERS, CPPIB (Canada), ABP (Netherlands), ATP (Denmark), and Ontario Teachers. Their scale and long investment horizons make them well-suited to PE''s illiquidity profile. Sovereign wealth funds, endowments, and insurance companies follow as major contributors.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'University endowments — particularly Yale under David Swensen — pioneered heavy allocations to private equity and alternatives. What was the underlying logic of the ''endowment model''?', '["Endowments had to invest in PE due to regulatory mandates","Endowments'' indefinite investment horizons allow them to capture illiquidity premiums that shorter-horizon investors cannot access","PE was the only asset class available to tax-exempt institutions","Endowments received special fee discounts from PE firms"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Swensen''s insight was that endowments have effectively perpetual time horizons and stable spending needs, unlike most institutions facing liability-matching constraints. This allows them to capture illiquidity premiums from PE, real assets, and other alternatives. Yale''s allocation shifted heavily toward alternatives starting in the 1990s, producing decades of outperformance and becoming the template for endowment investing globally.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Insurance companies are major LPs in PE but typically allocate smaller portfolio shares than endowments. What structural factor explains this difference?', '["Insurance companies are prohibited from investing in PE","Capital adequacy and regulatory capital requirements penalise illiquid investments, constraining PE allocation size","Insurance companies only invest in domestic PE","Insurance companies have shorter liability horizons than endowments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Insurance companies operate under regulatory capital frameworks (Solvency II in Europe, risk-based capital in the US) that require them to hold additional capital against illiquid investments. This raises the effective cost of PE allocation and caps the share of portfolio they can commit. Despite these constraints, insurance companies remain important LPs, particularly for private credit where duration matches their long-dated liabilities.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Single-family offices have become an increasingly important LP category. What distinguishes their approach from institutional LPs like pension funds?', '["Family offices receive higher fee discounts than institutional LPs","They have greater flexibility in portfolio construction and can commit quickly without institutional approval processes, but lack the scale of pension funds","They are legally prohibited from accessing institutional PE funds","They only invest in venture capital, not buyout funds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Family offices benefit from flexibility that institutional LPs lack: no investment committee process, faster decision-making, willingness to write smaller cheques, and openness to emerging managers. Individual family offices rarely match the scale of major pension funds, but collectively represent a large and growing share of LP capital. They are particularly important to first-time fund managers and niche strategies.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Funds of funds (FoF) raise capital from investors and commit it across multiple PE funds. What value proposition do they offer, and which investors do they primarily serve?', '["They guarantee higher returns than direct PE fund investment","They offer access, diversification, and manager selection expertise to investors who lack resources to build direct PE portfolios — typically smaller institutions and HNW individuals","They eliminate all PE fees through institutional relationships","They are only available to sovereign wealth funds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Funds of funds serve investors who want PE exposure but lack the scale, expertise, or resources to build direct portfolios: smaller institutions, HNW individuals, and some family offices. FoF provide access (leveraging relationships with top GPs), diversification (exposure to 20-50 funds), and manager selection. The cost is a second fee layer (FoF fees plus underlying fund fees), which reduces net returns.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Over the past decade, high-net-worth individuals have increasingly accessed PE through feeder funds and semi-liquid products. What change in the industry has enabled this shift?', '["PE regulations have been repealed, allowing anyone to invest","Development of semi-liquid fund structures (BDCs, interval funds, evergreen structures) with lower minimums and periodic redemption rights","PE firms have stopped raising institutional capital","HNW investors are now treated as institutional LPs by regulators"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Semi-liquid structures — business development companies (BDCs), interval funds, evergreen funds, tender offer funds — have made PE accessible to HNW and accredited retail channels. These structures feature lower minimums ($25K-$250K vs. $5M+), periodic redemption rights (subject to caps), and standardised reporting. This democratisation represents a large growth market for GPs.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A large institutional LP negotiates representation on the fund''s LP Advisory Committee (LPAC) as a condition of its commitment. What functions does the LPAC typically perform?', '["It approves every investment the GP proposes","It reviews conflicts of interest, valuation methodology, and governance matters, while generally respecting GP investment discretion","It directly manages the portfolio companies on behalf of LPs","It replaces the GP''s investment committee"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The LPAC provides LP oversight on governance matters: reviewing conflicts of interest, approving certain fund-level decisions (key-person events, term extensions), examining valuation methodology, and raising LP concerns. LPACs do not approve individual investments — that remains GP discretion. LPAC seats are typically reserved for the largest LPs and provide enhanced visibility into fund operations.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A large pension fund commits $200M to a PE fund and negotiates a side letter with provisions not available in the standard LPA. A ''Most Favoured Nation'' clause in the side letter provides what protection?', '["It guarantees the LP the highest returns among all LPs","It ensures the LP receives any more favourable terms granted to other LPs in the same fund","It requires the GP to exclude the LP from any losses","It gives the LP veto rights over fund decisions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MFN (Most Favoured Nation) clauses ensure that if the GP grants more favourable terms (lower fees, better reporting, co-investment priority) to another LP of similar or smaller size, those terms are extended to the MFN holder. This protects large LPs from being disadvantaged by side deals. MFN clauses have become standard for major institutional LPs and drive the market practice of uniform fund terms.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm allocates a portion of deal capital as ''co-investment'' opportunities to select LPs. What economic benefit does co-investment provide to the LP?', '["Co-investment capital is subject to higher fees than fund capital","Co-investment typically carries reduced or zero management fee and carried interest on the co-invested portion, lowering the effective blended cost","Co-investment provides veto rights over the main fund''s investment decisions","Co-investment is only available to retail investors"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Co-investment allocations let LPs invest additional capital alongside the fund in specific deals, typically with reduced fees (often fee-free and carry-free). This lowers the LP''s blended cost of PE exposure and provides concentrated exposure to specific deals they find attractive. Co-investment rights are a key negotiating lever for large LPs and a meaningful economic benefit.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Before committing capital to a new PE fund, an institutional LP typically conducts extensive due diligence on the GP. Which of the following is typically NOT a focus of LP due diligence?', '["Track record analysis of prior funds and individual deal attribution","Team stability, key-person risk, and succession planning","Operational infrastructure, compliance, and governance processes","The personal investment philosophy of the LP''s portfolio manager"]'::jsonb, 3, 'LP due diligence on GPs is extensive and typically covers: track record and attribution analysis, team and key-person risk, investment process and discipline, operational and compliance infrastructure, reference checks with portfolio company executives and other LPs, and ESG practices. The LP''s own investment philosophy is not part of GP due diligence — it shapes the LP''s selection criteria but is not evaluated about the GP.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A pension fund evaluating a third-time fund weighs track record, team stability, and strategy evolution. Which combination would most likely cause concern?', '["Strong Fund I returns, strong Fund II returns, and stable senior team","Strong Fund I, weak Fund II, and departure of two senior partners between Fund II and Fund III","Consistent returns across vintages with gradual strategy expansion","Strong returns combined with growing institutional LP base"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Inconsistent performance paired with senior departures is a classic warning signal. It raises questions about whether strong early performance was attributable to departed partners and whether the remaining team can repeat past success. LPs track individual deal attribution and team continuity carefully. A single weak vintage is recoverable if the team remains intact; both problems together substantially raise commitment risk.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Under PE ownership, the CEO of a portfolio company typically faces what combination of expectations that differs from owner-operator or public-company CEOs?', '["Lower performance expectations in exchange for longer tenure","Higher accountability to board and investors, but also significant equity upside through the Management Equity Programme","Complete autonomy from the PE owners","The same expectations as a public-company CEO"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE-backed CEOs operate under heightened accountability: monthly KPI reporting, active board engagement, explicit value creation plans, and willingness to replace underperformers. In exchange, they receive equity incentives (MEP) that can deliver life-changing wealth if the value creation plan succeeds. This high-accountability, high-reward dynamic is distinctive to PE and attracts a specific type of operator.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm negotiates a Management Equity Programme (MEP) with the CEO of a newly acquired company. What is the typical structure and purpose?', '["Management receives shares for free with no investment required","Management personally invests a meaningful amount (often 1-3 years of salary) and receives shares plus performance-linked ''sweet equity'' that rewards outperformance","The PE firm pays management a fixed bonus in cash at exit","Management receives publicly listed stock in the PE firm"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MEP structures require meaningful personal investment from management (often 1-3 years of salary) alongside performance-linked ''sweet equity'' that increases management''s share of proceeds if the PE firm exceeds specified return thresholds. Personal investment ensures skin in the game; sweet equity creates asymmetric upside that drives exceptional effort during the hold period.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm''s MEP includes a ''sweet equity'' structure that pays management a disproportionate share of returns above a specified IRR threshold. What is the purpose of this structure?', '["To minimise the PE firm''s own returns","To create asymmetric upside for management when they drive exceptional performance, while protecting the PE firm''s downside","To satisfy regulatory requirements for management compensation","To reduce taxes on the PE firm''s carry"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sweet equity works like a ratchet: if returns exceed specified thresholds (e.g., 25% IRR), management receives a larger share of proceeds above that level. This asymmetry aligns management with outperformance — they earn modestly if the deal works fine but spectacularly if they drive exceptional results. The PE firm retains the base return while incentivising management to push beyond adequate performance.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A CEO leaves a PE-backed company 18 months before exit. The MEP contains ''leaver provisions'' that depend on whether the departure is classified as ''good leaver'' or ''bad leaver.'' What typically defines this distinction?', '["Good leaver means the CEO left voluntarily; bad leaver means they were fired","Good leavers (death, disability, retirement, company dismissal without cause) typically receive fair value for their equity; bad leavers (resignation, dismissal for cause) may receive only cost","The distinction is personal and has no legal meaning","The classification is determined by the departing executive"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Leaver provisions create financial consequences for departure: good leavers (death, disability, retirement, termination without cause) receive fair value for their shares; bad leavers (resignation before vesting, termination for cause) receive only their original cost or a discounted amount. This structure incentivises management to stay and deliver, while protecting the PE firm from opportunistic departures.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm acquires a family-owned business where the founder served as both CEO and CFO. Which executive replacement is typically the first priority post-acquisition?', '["Replace the CEO immediately","Hire a professional CFO capable of supporting PE reporting standards, leverage management, and bolt-on integration","Replace the entire senior management team","No replacements are typically needed in the first year"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Professional CFO recruitment is almost always the first priority post-acquisition. Family-owned businesses often lack CFOs capable of managing leveraged balance sheets, producing monthly management accounts on deadline, supporting M&A diligence, and handling lender relationships. The CEO may remain if performing well; the CFO gap is usually more urgent and more solvable.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm requires the management team to co-invest personal capital into the deal. What does the PE firm primarily gain from this requirement?', '["Additional capital that reduces the PE firm''s equity commitment","A strong signal of management''s confidence in the business, plus alignment with PE returns","Tax benefits on the acquisition","Regulatory compliance for the transaction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Management co-investment (typically 1-3 years of salary) is less about raising capital and more about signal and alignment. Management willing to put meaningful personal capital at risk signals confidence in the business and the plan. It also creates genuine financial alignment with the PE firm''s returns. Reluctance to co-invest is a red flag that the PE firm should investigate before proceeding.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A sell-side investment bank is engaged by a business owner planning to sell to a PE firm. Whose interests does the banker primarily serve?', '["The eventual buyer''s, to ensure a fair purchase price","The seller''s, by running a competitive process that maximises valuation and deal terms","The regulator''s, to ensure deal compliance","Both sides equally in a fiduciary capacity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sell-side investment bankers are engaged by and work for the seller. Their job is to maximise sale price and deal terms for their client — typically through a competitive auction process that generates multiple bids. Buyers should never mistake a sell-side banker''s cooperation for neutrality; every action (timing, information access, bid structure) is designed to enhance seller outcomes.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'During PE due diligence, ''CDD'' and ''FDD'' are two distinct workstreams. What is the primary focus of each?', '["CDD covers legal due diligence; FDD covers financial due diligence","Commercial DD assesses market and competitive position; Financial DD validates the target''s financial performance through quality-of-earnings analysis","CDD covers compliance; FDD covers forensic investigation","Both terms refer to the same workstream"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Commercial DD (CDD) assesses market size, growth, competitive positioning, customer dynamics, and pricing power — typically conducted by management consultants (McKinsey, Bain, L.E.K., OC&C). Financial DD (FDD) validates reported and adjusted EBITDA through forensic quality-of-earnings analysis — typically by Big Four or specialist transaction advisory firms. Both are standard in PE processes.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'The Big Four (Deloitte, PwC, EY, KPMG) dominate PE financial due diligence work. What specialist alternatives exist, and when might a PE firm prefer them?', '["No alternatives exist; Big Four have a legal monopoly on FDD work","Specialist transaction advisory firms (Alvarez & Marsal, FTI Consulting, Duff & Phelps) offer deeper forensic expertise and are often preferred for complex or distressed situations","Specialist firms are only used for very small transactions","Specialist firms are used only by non-US PE firms"]'::jsonb, 1, 'While the Big Four handle the majority of PE FDD work, specialist firms (Alvarez & Marsal, FTI Consulting, Duff & Phelps, Houlihan Lokey) offer deeper forensic expertise, particularly for complex accounting, distressed situations, or highly technical industries. The choice depends on deal complexity, sector, and the PE firm''s relationships. Some PE firms prefer specialists for the hands-on involvement of senior partners.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A first-time fund manager is raising a debut $300M fund and engages a placement agent. What does the placement agent provide?', '["Legal advice on fund documentation","Access to institutional LP relationships and assistance with marketing and fundraising execution","Audit services for fund operations","Operational due diligence on portfolio companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Placement agents (Park Hill, Campbell Lutyens, MVision, Monument Group, Rede Partners) help GPs — particularly first-time managers — access institutional LP relationships, prepare fundraising materials, organise roadshows, and manage the fundraising process. They typically charge 1-2% of capital raised. Established managers with existing LP bases may use placement agents for specific geographies or to supplement in-house IR teams.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm engages ''sponsor counsel'' — a law firm representing the PE fund''s interests — on every deal. What is the sponsor counsel''s primary role?', '["Representing the target company in negotiations","Structuring the acquisition, negotiating the SPA, and documenting the fund''s governance and financing arrangements","Conducting independent valuation of the target","Providing accounting services for the transaction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Sponsor counsel represents the PE fund across the deal lifecycle: transaction structure (acquisition vehicle, debt placement), SPA negotiation (warranties, indemnities, conditions precedent), financing documentation, regulatory matters, and post-closing governance. Major sponsor counsel firms include Kirkland & Ellis, Simpson Thacher, Weil Gotshal, Latham & Watkins, Clifford Chance, Allen & Overy, and Linklaters.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'During commercial due diligence, ''voice of the customer'' interviews — direct conversations between CDD advisers and the target''s customers — are considered particularly valuable. Why?', '["Customers are legally required to provide honest information to CDD advisers","Customer interviews provide unfiltered feedback about product, pricing, and competitive alternatives that management''s narrative may not fully reflect","Customers determine the final purchase price","Customers have access to the target''s confidential financial data"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Voice-of-customer interviews (15-30 typical in a CDD) provide unfiltered signal about the target''s competitive position, pricing power, customer satisfaction, and switching risk. Because customers are independent of management, their feedback often surfaces insights that contradict or qualify management''s narrative. A customer citing strong alternatives or deteriorating service quality is a material finding even if financials look strong.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'The senior bank lender in a mid-market LBO provides the largest tranche of the debt financing, typically at the lowest cost. What protections does this lender demand in exchange?', '["A minority equity stake in the target","Senior position in the capital structure, first-lien security over assets, and financial covenants that protect against deteriorating performance","Veto rights over the PE firm''s investment decisions","Representation on the portfolio company''s board"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Senior bank lenders (or syndicates of lenders) receive: senior position in the capital structure (paid before subordinated creditors), first-lien security over the target''s assets (providing collateral protection), and financial covenants (leverage ratio, interest coverage, cash flow tests). In exchange for these protections, they lend at the lowest cost of any capital in the structure. Covenants give lenders early intervention rights if performance deteriorates.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'Private credit direct lenders have grown dramatically as LBO financing providers. What competitive advantage do they offer PE borrowers versus traditional bank lenders?', '["Lower interest rates than any other debt source","Speed, certainty of execution, bespoke structuring (unitranche, PIK, junior capital), and single-lender relationships that simplify negotiations","Regulatory exemptions from all debt restrictions","Government-subsidised lending terms"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Private credit direct lenders (Ares, Blackstone Credit, Apollo Credit, Golub, Antares) compete on speed, execution certainty, and flexibility rather than price. They can underwrite and commit quickly, provide unitranche and bespoke structures, and handle complex situations (carve-outs, growth businesses, larger holds) that syndicated loan markets may reject. Their cost is typically 100-300 bps higher than comparable syndicated loans, which PE firms accept for the execution advantages.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'In an LBO capital structure, mezzanine debt occupies what position, and what economic features distinguish it from senior debt?', '["Senior to bank debt, with cash interest only","Junior to senior debt but senior to equity, typically with higher interest rates, warrants, and PIK features","An equity investment that pays no interest","A government-sponsored lending programme"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Mezzanine debt sits between senior debt and equity: subordinated to senior lenders in the priority waterfall but senior to equity. It typically carries 10-14% interest rates (vs. 5-8% for senior debt), often includes PIK (payment-in-kind) features that accrue rather than pay cash, and may include warrants for equity participation. Mezzanine is used when senior debt alone cannot fund the deal but pure equity would be too expensive.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A unitranche lender provides a single debt facility combining senior and subordinated debt features. What advantage does this structure offer PE borrowers?', '["It is the cheapest form of LBO financing available","It simplifies execution by providing one lender, one set of documents, and faster closing than arranging separate senior and mezzanine tranches","It eliminates the need for due diligence on the target","It provides unlimited availability regardless of leverage"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unitranche facilities combine what would otherwise be separate senior and mezzanine tranches into a single loan with a blended interest rate. The advantages are execution: one lender relationship, one set of documentation, faster closing, and simpler negotiations. The cost is higher than pure senior debt but lower than senior-plus-mezzanine separately. Unitranche has become the dominant financing structure for European mid-market LBOs.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'The syndicated leveraged loan market finances many large LBOs. What does ''syndication'' mean in this context?', '["The borrower receives loans from multiple countries simultaneously","An arranging bank underwrites the loan, then distributes portions to multiple institutional investors (CLOs, loan mutual funds, other banks)","The borrower must refinance the loan every year","The loan is converted to equity upon signing"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Syndication is the process where an arranging bank (JPMorgan, Goldman Sachs, Bank of America, Barclays, Deutsche Bank) commits to underwrite a large loan, then distributes portions to multiple institutional buyers. The final loan may have 50+ lenders, dominated by CLOs, loan mutual funds, and other institutional investors. Syndication allows loans of €500M+ to be funded and creates liquidity in the secondary loan market.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'key-players', 'A PE firm''s deal team on a mid-market acquisition typically consists of a partner, a VP, and one or two junior professionals (associate and analyst). How is workload typically distributed across this team?', '["Partners do all the modelling while juniors observe","Juniors build the financial model and conduct data room analysis; VPs manage workstreams and adviser coordination; partners lead strategy, negotiations, and IC presentation","All team members perform identical tasks","External advisers handle all analytical work"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE deal teams operate with distinct role definitions: juniors (analysts and associates) own the financial model, data room analysis, and detailed diligence; VPs and principals manage workstreams, coordinate external advisers, and drive the day-to-day process; partners lead strategic thinking, negotiation with the seller, IC presentation, and final decisions. This structure allows efficient work allocation while developing junior talent toward eventual partner roles.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A family office is considering two investment options: buying shares of a publicly listed industrial conglomerate or committing capital to a private equity buyout fund. Which feature most fundamentally distinguishes the PE commitment from the public share purchase?', '["The PE commitment requires a higher minimum investment amount","The PE commitment locks up capital for years with no ability to redeem at will","The PE commitment involves less risk because private companies are more stable","The PE commitment generates dividend income rather than capital gains"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Illiquidity is the defining structural difference. Public shares can be sold on any trading day; PE commitments lock capital for 5–10 years. This illiquidity is why PE historically demands a return premium over public markets, not because the underlying businesses are riskier or safer on average.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A large pension fund is comparing its PE portfolio''s 15-year net IRR of 13.5% to a public index return of 10.2% over the same period. Which of the following best explains why the pension fund accepts the operational complexity and illiquidity of PE in exchange for this return differential?', '["Public markets are inherently riskier than PE, so PE naturally earns more","The return premium compensates for capital being locked up for 5–10+ years (illiquidity premium)","PE funds are less volatile year-to-year, making them safer overall","Regulatory protections force PE funds to outperform public indices"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE funds lock up committed capital for 5–10+ years, during which LPs cannot redeem. The return premium compensates for this illiquidity and for the concentrated, undiversified nature of PE holdings. Public markets are not inherently riskier; PE interim valuations appear smoother only because they are marked quarterly rather than traded continuously.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A founder who sold his business to a PE firm complains that the new owners ''interfere constantly'' with strategic decisions, hiring, and capital allocation. His prior experience with public shareholders involved only voting at the AGM. What does this contrast most accurately illustrate?', '["PE firms typically micromanage portfolio companies in ways that destroy value","Public shareholders and PE owners operate under fundamentally different governance models: passive minority versus active majority","PE firms have weaker legal rights than public shareholders, forcing them to interfere","The founder should have negotiated stronger governance protections in the sale"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Public shareholders typically hold minority stakes, lack operational influence, and interact through boards and AGMs. PE firms hold controlling stakes, sit on the board, and work actively with management to implement the value creation plan. The active engagement the founder experiences is central to how PE generates returns, not an aberration.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A PE fund structures its investments with a 5–7 year hold target, rejecting both shorter trading strategies (1–2 years) and longer permanent capital approaches (20+ years). What is the primary structural reason for this medium-term horizon?', '["Tax regulations mandate a 5–7 year minimum hold before capital gains treatment applies","Operational transformations typically take 3–5 years to execute and validate before commanding exit premiums","Lenders require a specific maturity structure that aligns with 5–7 year holds","Insurance companies demand this exit timeline as an LP condition"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Real operational transformation takes time: cost programmes, bolt-on integrations, commercial strategy shifts. Selling earlier rarely captures full value; holding longer ties up LP capital that could be redeployed. The 5–7 year window matches how long it takes for a PE thesis to play out in practice.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Comparing a buyer evaluating a publicly listed retailer to a PE firm evaluating a private industrial target, which statement best describes the information environment each faces?', '["Both have equal access to audited quarterly financials and management guidance","The public buyer relies on standardised regulatory disclosures; the PE buyer has access to deeper proprietary data under NDA but must construct the picture through active diligence","Private companies are legally required to disclose the same information as public ones","Information access is identical; only valuation methods differ"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Public companies publish extensive standardised disclosures (quarterly reports, earnings calls, regulatory filings). Private companies face no equivalent obligation. PE firms gain access through NDAs and due diligence, often getting deeper insight than public analysts, but must actively build the picture from management accounts, customer interviews, and operational data.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A public company trades at 14x EBITDA. A PE firm acquires the same business through a take-private transaction at 16x EBITDA. Why is the PE firm willing to pay a premium over the public market price?', '["PE firms are less disciplined than public investors and systematically overpay","Taking a company private eliminates regulatory reporting costs, which justifies the premium on its own","The PE firm gains operational control to implement changes that public minority shareholders cannot drive","The premium represents the tax benefit of PE ownership"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The control premium reflects the value of implementing changes that public minority shareholders cannot. PE ownership enables capital structure optimisation, strategic pivots, cost programmes, and M&A on timelines that public boards rarely match. This control premium is integral to how PE can pay above-market prices and still generate returns.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A PE firm acquires a business at 9x EBITDA of €40M, grows EBITDA to €55M over five years, exits at 10x EBITDA, and repays €80M of debt during the hold period. Which value creation levers contributed to the return?', '["Only EBITDA growth, because the exit multiple is nearly identical to the entry multiple","EBITDA growth, modest multiple expansion, and debt paydown — all three","Only debt paydown, because the business value was essentially unchanged","Multiple expansion alone, since the entry and exit multiples differ"]'::jsonb, 1, 'All three classic LBO return drivers are present: EBITDA growth (€40M to €55M), multiple expansion (9x to 10x), and debt paydown (€80M). The strongest PE returns combine all three. Even a one-turn multiple move contributes meaningful value on a €55M EBITDA base.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A post-mortem review of a successful PE investment shows the return was generated 40% by EBITDA growth, 30% by debt paydown, 20% by multiple expansion, and 10% by interim dividend recapitalisations. What does this attribution most likely indicate?', '["The deal relied heavily on leverage and should be considered unusually risky","Multiple expansion was the primary driver, reflecting favourable market timing","The return was earned through a diversified combination of operational, financial, and market factors, characteristic of a well-executed modern deal","The attribution suggests the PE firm got lucky rather than adding genuine value"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Modern successful PE deals rarely rely on a single return driver. A balanced combination of operational improvement, financial engineering, and market dynamics is characteristic of durable performance. Over-reliance on any single lever, especially multiple expansion alone, is fragile because it depends on factors outside the PE firm''s control.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'At its most fundamental level, what distinguishes the PE business model from traditional public market investing?', '["PE firms hold for longer periods than public investors","PE firms actively manage businesses to improve them before selling, rather than passively holding for appreciation","PE firms have better access to information than public investors","PE firms use more leverage than public investors"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE is fundamentally an active ownership strategy: buying businesses with the explicit intention of improving them operationally and strategically, then selling. Public investing is primarily about selecting well-run businesses to passively hold. The longer horizons, better information, and leverage are all consequences of this active ownership model rather than the defining feature.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A PE professional distinguishes between ''high-quality'' and ''low-quality'' returns in post-deal attribution analysis. Which return profile would generally be considered higher quality?', '["A 3.0x MOIC generated primarily by multiple expansion (entry at 8x, exit at 13x) with flat EBITDA","A 3.0x MOIC generated primarily by EBITDA growth, with EBITDA doubling during the hold and stable multiples","A 3.0x MOIC generated primarily by leverage paydown with no underlying business improvement","A 3.0x MOIC generated entirely through recapitalisation dividends before any operational change"]'::jsonb, 1, 'EBITDA-driven returns reflect genuine operational value creation by the PE firm and management. Multiple expansion-driven returns depend on market conditions, credit cycles, and exit timing — factors outside the PE firm''s control. EBITDA growth is more repeatable, more defensible, and more indicative of the firm''s skill.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A PE firm''s 2010s deal portfolio generated a 22% IRR, while its 1980s-era funds generated 28% IRR despite having weaker operational capabilities at the time. What most likely explains the narrower return premium in the modern era?', '["Modern PE firms use less leverage than 1980s deals","Increased competition for deals has compressed entry multiples, reducing the pricing advantage available to a disciplined buyer","Modern deals are inherently more complex and therefore less profitable","Regulatory constraints limit modern returns"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The 1980s PE era had few competitors, fragmented target markets, and inefficient pricing. Modern PE faces intense competition from thousands of firms, sophisticated intermediaries, and well-informed sellers. Competition compresses the entry-multiple advantage that drove outsized 1980s returns. Modern firms compensate through operational capabilities, sector specialisation, and proprietary deal flow.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A financier in the 1960s-70s developed a technique of acquiring family-owned businesses using a mix of equity and debt, improving them operationally, and selling them profitably. He called this ''bootstrapping.'' This pioneering approach is most directly associated with:', '["The founding of Apollo Global Management","Jerome Kohlberg at Bear Stearns, who later co-founded KKR","Warren Buffett''s approach at Berkshire Hathaway","Michael Milken''s work at Drexel Burnham Lambert"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Jerome Kohlberg pioneered the bootstrapping buyout structure at Bear Stearns in the 1960s-70s, applying leverage and operational improvement to acquire family-owned businesses. In 1976 he left Bear Stearns with Henry Kravis and George Roberts to found KKR. Milken''s work on high-yield debt markets came later and served a different function (financing), not deal sourcing and structuring.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Why is the 1976 founding of KKR considered a foundational moment in private equity history?', '["It was the first PE firm to invest in technology companies","It established the independent leveraged buyout firm as a distinct institutional category separate from investment banks","It marked the first time US regulators recognised PE as a distinct asset class","It introduced the 2-and-20 fee structure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Before KKR, leveraged buyouts were executed as one-off transactions by investment bankers, corporations, or wealthy individuals. KKR established the dedicated, independent LBO firm model: a permanent capital-raising vehicle focused on executing multiple buyouts across vintages. This institutional form defined the industry and was replicated by hundreds of firms.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'In the 1980s LBO boom, three conditions converged to enable the era''s mega-deals. Which of the following was NOT one of them?', '["The maturation of the high-yield bond market, pioneered by Michael Milken","Deregulation of financial markets that expanded credit availability","The breakup of diversified conglomerates that created undervalued targets","Widespread institutional LP allocations from pension funds and sovereign wealth funds"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Institutional LP bases were relatively underdeveloped in the 1980s. Pension funds and sovereign wealth funds formalised their PE allocations mostly in the 1990s and 2000s. The three enabling 1980s conditions were high-yield debt markets, deregulation, and conglomerate breakups providing acquisition targets.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'During the 1980s LBO boom, large diversified conglomerates were common PE acquisition targets. Why did these entities create particularly attractive deal opportunities?', '["Conglomerates had the strongest management teams, making them easier to operate","The sum of the individual divisions, when sold separately, often exceeded the conglomerate''s market value, allowing PE firms to profit by breaking them up","Conglomerates paid higher dividends than focused companies","Conglomerates had no antitrust exposure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Many 1980s conglomerates traded at a ''conglomerate discount'': the market valued the combined entity at less than the sum of its divisions. PE firms acquired them, broke them into standalone business units, and sold each to strategic acquirers who paid fair value for focused assets. This arbitrage was a defining deal strategy of the era.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'KKR''s 1989 acquisition of RJR Nabisco for approximately $25 billion is often cited as emblematic of the 1980s PE era. What does the deal most represent in industry history?', '["The first successful bolt-on acquisition strategy","The culmination of the 1980s mega-LBO era in terms of scale, financial engineering, and public attention","The first PE exit via IPO","The first cross-border PE transaction"]'::jsonb, 1, 'RJR Nabisco was at the time the largest corporate transaction ever completed. It featured aggressive financial engineering, dramatic bidding wars, and significant controversy about executive incentives. The book ''Barbarians at the Gate'' captured both the transaction and the cultural moment, making RJR Nabisco the defining PE deal of the decade.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'The early 1990s forced significant changes in the PE industry. What was the most important strategic shift that emerged from this period?', '["PE firms started investing primarily in technology companies","Firms began emphasising operational value creation rather than relying solely on financial engineering and leverage","PE funds shifted toward shorter hold periods to improve IRR","The 2-and-20 fee structure was abandoned in favour of fixed fees"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The collapse of the junk bond market, a recession, and several over-leveraged failures forced the industry to rebuild credibility. Simply buying, leveraging, and flipping became insufficient. PE firms began building dedicated sector expertise, operational capabilities, and longer-term value creation playbooks, a shift that continues to define the industry''s approach today.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Which of the following best describes how the LP base changed during the 1990s?', '["Individual accredited investors replaced institutions as the dominant source of capital","Institutional investors (pension funds, endowments, sovereign wealth funds) formalised their PE allocations, creating a stable institutional base","LP capital commitments became shorter in duration","Hedge funds replaced pension funds as the primary LP category"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The 1990s marked the institutionalisation of the PE LP base. Pension funds, endowments (following Yale''s lead under David Swensen), and sovereign wealth funds formalised target allocations to PE, creating a stable and growing pool of institutional capital. This institutional base shaped the professional PE industry we know today.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'KKR''s acquisition of Hilton Hotels in 2007 ultimately generated approximately $14 billion in profit, making it one of the most profitable PE deals ever. What was the primary driver of this outcome?', '["Financial engineering through aggressive leverage and multiple dividend recapitalisations","Operational transformation of Hilton into an asset-light franchise model with an expanded brand portfolio","Favourable market timing — Hilton was acquired near a market low","Currency arbitrage from international operations"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Despite being acquired near the pre-2008 market peak and surviving the global financial crisis, Hilton generated extraordinary returns through genuine operational transformation. KKR shifted Hilton from asset-heavy hotel ownership to a franchise-driven, asset-light model with a dramatically expanded brand portfolio and international footprint. The 11-year hold allowed the thesis to play out fully.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'The 2007 acquisition of TXU (now Vistra Energy) by a consortium of KKR, TPG, and Goldman Sachs for $45 billion is often cited as a cautionary tale in PE history. What was the primary reason for the deal''s poor outcome?', '["Regulatory intervention blocked the planned restructuring","The deal thesis depended on natural gas prices remaining high, which collapsed due to the shale revolution","Antitrust regulators forced divestitures that eliminated value creation potential","Management turnover destabilised the business post-acquisition"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The TXU thesis depended on natural gas prices remaining elevated, which would support high electricity prices and the company''s cash flows. The shale gas revolution drove natural gas prices sharply lower, collapsing electricity prices and the deal''s economics. The company ultimately filed for bankruptcy. TXU illustrates the risk of mega-deals built on macro thesis rather than controllable operational improvement.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'During the 2008 financial crisis, many observers expected PE funds to experience forced selling similar to what happened in public markets. This did not happen. Why was PE more resilient than expected?', '["PE funds had no exposure to the sectors affected by the crisis","The long-term committed capital structure insulated PE from the need to sell at distressed prices","PE firms received direct bailout support from central banks","Regulatory forbearance suspended all debt covenants during the crisis"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PE''s closed-end fund structure gives GPs multi-year capital commitments from LPs that cannot be withdrawn on demand. This insulates PE from the forced selling that affects mutual funds and hedge funds facing redemptions during market stress. Firms with dry powder could acquire distressed assets at low prices, turning the crisis into opportunity.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Following the 2008 financial crisis, which US regulatory change most directly affected PE firms?', '["The Sarbanes-Oxley Act required PE firms to use IFRS reporting","The Dodd-Frank Act required larger PE firms to register as investment advisers with the SEC, increasing reporting and compliance obligations","The Volcker Rule prohibited banks from lending to PE-backed companies","The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act prohibited PE firms from raising international capital"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The Dodd-Frank Act of 2010 required PE firms with $150M+ in AUM to register as investment advisers with the SEC. This registration brought PE under periodic SEC examination, required written compliance programmes, and introduced regular regulatory reporting (Form PF). It remains the core regulatory framework for US-based firms.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A US-based PE firm plans to market its fund to European institutional investors. Which regulatory framework will most directly affect its ability to do so?', '["The EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)","The Alternative Investment Fund Managers Directive (AIFMD)","The Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II)","The European Central Bank''s Solvency II framework"]'::jsonb, 1, 'AIFMD is the primary EU regulatory framework governing PE fund managers operating in or marketing to European investors. Non-EU managers marketing into the EU must comply with national private placement regimes and satisfy AIFMD requirements. The regime imposes registration, reporting, remuneration, and depositary requirements. AIFMD II extends these rules from 2026.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Since 2007, several major PE firms (Blackstone, KKR, Apollo, Carlyle, EQT, CVC) have completed IPOs of their own firms. What does this trend most directly represent?', '["PE firms needed emergency capital to avoid insolvency during the 2008 crisis","The transformation of PE firms from private partnerships into diversified alternative asset managers serving retail and institutional investors","Regulatory requirements forcing PE firms to disclose partner compensation","A temporary phase that has since been reversed"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The IPO trend reflects PE firms'' transformation from deal-doing partnerships into diversified alternative asset managers. Public listings provide permanent capital, acquisition currency for building credit and real assets platforms, and access to the retail wealth channel. The listed firms are now multi-strategy alternative platforms, with PE as one product among many.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A pension fund evaluating Blackstone today would find the firm offers strategies across which of the following categories?', '["Only traditional leveraged buyout funds","Leveraged buyouts, real estate, private credit, infrastructure, secondaries, and other alternative strategies","Only public equity index funds","Only venture capital funds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Modern mega-firms like Blackstone operate multi-strategy platforms spanning buyouts, real estate (the largest individual strategy for Blackstone), private credit, infrastructure, hedge fund solutions, secondaries, and insurance-linked strategies. Diversification serves both LP demand for one-stop alternatives access and the GP''s strategic interests in broader fee base.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A European mid-market PE firm describes itself as ''operating in the upper mid-market.'' What characteristic most accurately fits this positioning?', '["Acquires businesses with $1–5 million of EBITDA using sector-focused strategies","Manages $50 billion or more in AUM and competes for the largest global deals","Operates with $5–50 billion in AUM and often builds concentrated sector-specialist portfolios","Invests exclusively in venture-stage technology companies with no leverage"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Upper mid-market firms typically manage $5–50 billion in AUM and frequently operate as sector specialists with deep operational capabilities. Mega-funds sit above this tier ($50B+), while lower mid-market firms operate below $1B AUM. Venture investing is a separate asset class.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Global private equity assets under management have reached which approximate scale as of recent years?', '["Approximately $500 billion","Approximately $2 trillion","Approximately $8 trillion or more","Approximately $50 trillion"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The global PE industry manages approximately $8 trillion or more in AUM across all strategies (buyouts, growth, credit, real assets, secondaries). This has grown from roughly $500 billion in the early 2000s. The largest individual firms each manage over $500 billion. This scale reflects decades of institutional LP flows and the industry''s expansion into adjacent strategies.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Industry dry powder — uncalled committed LP capital — has reached approximately $3.7 trillion globally. What does a high level of dry powder typically indicate?', '["PE firms are struggling to raise new capital","A competitive deal environment with significant pressure to deploy capital, which can drive higher entry multiples","PE funds have failed to generate acceptable returns","The asset class is in structural decline"]'::jsonb, 1, 'High dry powder signals both strong LP confidence (willing to commit large amounts) and deployment challenges (many buyers chasing limited attractive deals). The practical consequence is competitive tension that pushes entry multiples higher, compressing forward-looking returns. Dry powder is simultaneously a measure of industry health and a warning about discipline.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A retail investor with $250,000 in savings was historically unable to access private equity. Recent structural shifts have begun to change this. Which of the following best describes the democratisation trend?', '["PE firms are acquiring banks so retail investors can access funds through checking accounts","Semi-liquid PE products and non-traded BDCs are allowing accredited retail and HNW investors to access alternatives with periodic liquidity","Governments have repealed accredited investor rules entirely","PE firms have lowered minimum fund commitments to $10,000"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The democratisation trend involves semi-liquid structures (interval funds, BDCs, evergreen funds) that provide periodic redemption rights and lower minimums, making PE exposure available to accredited retail investors and HNW channels. This represents a large growth opportunity for GPs seeking to diversify their LP base beyond traditional institutions. It does not eliminate illiquidity entirely or change accredited investor rules.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Over the past decade, private credit has grown into one of the largest segments within alternative asset management. What structural shift most directly enabled this growth?', '["Central bank purchases of private credit securities","Banks retreating from middle-market lending post-2008, creating a gap filled by direct lenders","The repeal of Basel III capital requirements","Government subsidies for private credit funds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Post-2008 banking regulations (Basel III, Dodd-Frank) increased capital requirements on banks holding leveraged loans, reducing their appetite for middle-market lending. Direct lenders filled this gap by providing unitranche and other flexible loan products directly to PE-backed companies. Private credit has grown from a niche strategy to over $1.5 trillion in global AUM.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'In recent years, the technology sector has become the single largest category of PE deal activity. What characteristic of technology businesses makes them particularly attractive to PE buyers?', '["Technology companies rarely require capital investment, reducing capex risk","Recurring subscription revenue produces predictable cash flows that support leverage, and high gross margins enable rapid operational improvement","Technology companies face no competitive pressure","Regulatory environments universally favour technology sector acquisitions"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Software and tech-enabled businesses often combine recurring subscription revenue (predictable cash flows that support leverage), high gross margins (enabling margin expansion), and strong market positions (switching costs, network effects). These characteristics match the ideal LBO candidate profile. Firms like Thoma Bravo, Vista Equity Partners, and Silver Lake have built platforms entirely focused on software PE.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'An LP receives notice that the GP is proposing to transfer one portfolio company from the current fund (entering year 10) into a new vehicle. The LP can either roll into the new vehicle or cash out at fair value. What is this structure called, and why is it growing?', '["A secondary buyout, growing because of hedge fund demand","A GP-led continuation vehicle, growing because it allows GPs to retain high-performing assets beyond fund life while giving LPs liquidity optionality","A recapitalisation, growing because interest rates are falling","A tender offer, growing because of retail investor demand"]'::jsonb, 1, 'GP-led continuation vehicles allow GPs to extend ownership of high-performing portfolio companies beyond the original fund''s life. Existing LPs get optionality: cash out at fair value or roll into the new vehicle with fresh terms. These structures have grown to over $50 billion annually, driven by LPs seeking liquidity, GPs retaining star assets, and secondary buyers providing fresh capital.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Average PE hold periods have extended from approximately 4 years in the mid-2000s to over 5.5 years today. Which factors have most contributed to this shift?', '["LPs are demanding shorter hold periods, but GPs ignore the requests","A combination of longer operational transformations, weaker exit markets in some vintages, and the growth of continuation vehicles","Regulatory requirements now mandate minimum 5-year holds","Tax law changes have made shorter holds uneconomic"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Longer holds reflect structural shifts: operational value creation takes longer than financial engineering; exit markets have been periodically weaker (2022-2024 particularly); buy-and-build strategies require time to execute fully; and continuation vehicles extend ownership of high-performing assets. Regulatory changes have not driven this trend, and LPs generally prefer faster distributions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Over the past decade, large institutional LPs have concentrated their PE allocations among fewer GP relationships, often committing larger amounts to a smaller number of firms. This trend most benefits which group?', '["New and emerging first-time fund managers","Established large firms with proven track records, who can absorb larger commitments from top LPs","Retail investors accessing PE through semi-liquid products","Regional boutique firms focused on single markets"]'::jsonb, 1, 'LP consolidation — fewer GP relationships per LP, larger commitments per relationship — systematically favours large established firms with proven track records, deep operational capabilities, and ability to absorb $500M+ commitments. New and emerging firms face greater fundraising challenges as LPs concentrate capital with known quantities. This widens the gap between top-tier and second-tier firms.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A European institutional LP asks whether a new fund is classified as Article 6, 8, or 9 under SFDR. What is this LP trying to understand?', '["The fund''s pass-through tax status","The fund''s sustainability and ESG disclosure classification","The fund''s licensing arrangements with regulators","The fund''s fee structure"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The EU Sustainable Finance Disclosure Regulation (SFDR) requires funds to classify themselves: Article 6 (no specific sustainability integration), Article 8 (promotes environmental or social characteristics), or Article 9 (has sustainable investment as its objective). The classification affects disclosure, marketing, and LP due diligence. European institutional LPs increasingly require Article 8 or Article 9 classification as a prerequisite for investment.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Approximately what share of global PE activity (by deal volume and AUM) is concentrated in North America?', '["Approximately 25-30%","Approximately 55-60%","Approximately 85-90%","Approximately 10-15%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'North America (primarily the United States) accounts for roughly 55-60% of global PE AUM and deal volume. This dominance reflects deeper US capital markets, the large institutional LP base, and the concentration of the world''s largest PE firms in New York and other major US cities. Europe accounts for 25-30%, Asia-Pacific 15-20%, and other regions the remainder.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'The Nordic region (Sweden, Denmark, Norway, Finland) has produced a disproportionately large number of globally significant PE firms relative to its population. Which factors most contribute to this strength?', '["Government subsidies for domestic PE firms","A combination of institutional LP maturity, strong engineering and technology talent, and deep family-business markets needing succession solutions","Lower corporate tax rates than other European countries","Proximity to US capital markets"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The Nordic PE strength reflects several structural factors: sophisticated institutional LP base (AP funds in Sweden, ATP in Denmark, GPFG in Norway); strong technology and healthcare sectors; deep mid-market of family-owned businesses needing succession; and a culture of professional governance and transparency. Firms like EQT, Nordic Capital, Altor, IK Partners, and Hg have Nordic roots and strong track records.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Which of the following is a characteristic difference between European and US PE markets?', '["European deals use substantially more leverage than US deals","European markets have historically featured more conservative leverage, more family-owned targets, and a stronger regulatory overlay","European PE focuses only on technology sectors","European markets have no mid-market PE activity"]'::jsonb, 1, 'European PE historically features lower entry leverage (4.5-5.5x vs. 5.5-6.5x in the US), a greater proportion of family-owned and privately-held targets, and significant regulatory overlay (AIFMD, GDPR, sustainability reporting). These differences reflect different credit markets, ownership patterns, and regulatory environments. The gap has narrowed but remains meaningful.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'A mid-market European PE firm focuses its sourcing strategy on family-owned businesses facing succession questions. Why is this a particularly attractive segment for European PE?', '["Family-owned businesses are legally required to sell to PE firms","Europe has a deep base of founder-owned mid-market companies where the next generation is often unwilling or unable to continue, creating PE buying opportunities","Family-owned businesses always pay higher multiples than listed companies","Tax regulations favour PE acquisitions of family businesses"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Continental Europe — particularly Germany (Mittelstand), but also France, Italy, Nordics — has a large base of founder-owned and family-owned mid-market businesses. When the next generation is unwilling or unable to run the business, succession often requires an external solution. PE firms with relationship-driven sourcing can identify these opportunities before they reach formal auction, often securing proprietary access.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'pe-fundamentals', 'Over the past two decades, sovereign wealth funds from the Gulf states, Norway, and Singapore have become among the most significant LP categories. What structural advantages do they bring as investors?', '["They have the shortest investment horizons of any LP category","They bring enormous capital, long investment horizons, and ability to co-invest directly alongside GPs","They are exempt from all due diligence requirements","They only invest in domestic PE funds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'SWFs bring three distinct advantages: massive committable capital (individual funds manage hundreds of billions to over a trillion); indefinite investment horizons (no liabilities forcing withdrawal); and sophisticated direct-investment capabilities that allow them to co-invest alongside GPs. They are increasingly active not just as LPs but also as direct deal participants.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'Two investments both generate a 3.0x MOIC. Investment A returns capital in 4 years; Investment B returns capital in 9 years. Which is more attractive and why?', '["Investment B — longer holds demonstrate stronger operational transformation","Investment A — faster return generates a higher IRR and frees capital for redeployment","They are equally attractive — MOIC is the definitive measure of PE performance","Investment B — longer hold periods command premium exit multiples"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Both investments generate the same absolute multiple (3.0x), but Investment A delivers roughly 32% annualised returns versus approximately 13% for Investment B. Time matters because capital returned earlier can be redeployed. This is why MOIC alone is insufficient — it must be paired with IRR to evaluate PE performance.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund reports a gross IRR of 25% and a net IRR of 17%. What primarily explains the 8 percentage point gap?', '["Taxes paid at the fund level before distribution to LPs","Management fees and carried interest paid to the GP","Currency translation losses on international investments","Valuation write-downs of underperforming portfolio companies"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The gap between gross and net IRR reflects the GP''s economic take: 2% annual management fees plus 20% carried interest on profits above the hurdle. The typical spread is 3-7 percentage points for well-performing funds, though it varies with fund size and fee structure. PE funds are pass-through entities for tax purposes in most jurisdictions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An LP is comparing two PE funds approaching year 6. Fund Alpha reports TVPI of 2.2x with DPI of 0.4x. Fund Beta reports TVPI of 1.9x with DPI of 1.3x. Which fund''s performance is more certain and why?', '["Fund Alpha — higher TVPI means superior total value creation","Fund Beta — most of its reported value has been realised as actual cash distributions","Both are equally certain since TVPI captures total fund performance","Fund Alpha — the larger unrealised portion indicates greater growth potential"]'::jsonb, 1, 'DPI measures actual cash returned to LPs; RVPI (the difference between TVPI and DPI) is unrealised paper value that can deteriorate before exit. Fund Beta has distributed most of its value (1.3x of its 1.9x TVPI is realised), making its track record more certain. Fund Alpha''s 2.2x TVPI depends heavily on unrealised valuations that must still be achieved through exits.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm reports an impressive 28% IRR on its latest fund. A sophisticated LP asks for the fund''s Public Market Equivalent (PME) benchmark. What question is the LP trying to answer?', '["Whether the fund''s returns would have qualified for a stock market listing","How the fund''s returns compare to investing the same cash flows in a public index","Whether the fund''s valuations have been audited against public company standards","How the fund''s IRR compares to the GP''s historical track record"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PME benchmarks PE returns against what an equivalent investment in a public index would have earned on the same cash flow dates. A PME above 1.0x means the PE fund outperformed the benchmark; below 1.0x means a passive index would have done better. A 28% IRR during a strong bull market may reflect beta rather than genuine alpha.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'What does the Internal Rate of Return (IRR) actually measure in a PE context?', '["The total profit earned as a percentage of invested capital","The annualised rate of return that equates the present value of all cash inflows to the present value of all cash outflows","The simple average of annual returns over the holding period","The ratio of exit proceeds to initial investment"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IRR is the discount rate that makes the net present value of all cash flows (both outflows and inflows) equal to zero. In PE, it captures both the absolute return and the time value of money — an IRR of 20% means the investment compounded at 20% annually across all cash flows. This sensitivity to timing is what makes IRR different from MOIC.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund assumes an investment will generate a 22% IRR over a 5-year hold. What is a critical limitation of using IRR to evaluate this projection?', '["IRR does not account for the size of the investment","IRR implicitly assumes that interim cash flows can be reinvested at the same high rate (the ''reinvestment assumption''), which is rarely achievable in practice","IRR cannot be calculated without audited financial statements","IRR is always lower than the actual return"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IRR''s key limitation is the reinvestment assumption: the calculation mathematically assumes any interim cash flows earn the same IRR rate. In practice, capital returned in Year 2 rarely earns 22% when redeployed. This is why sophisticated LPs use Modified IRR (MIRR) or focus on MOIC alongside IRR. The assumption matters most for deals with heavy interim distributions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm invests €50M in a portfolio company and exits 6 years later for €200M total proceeds. What is the approximate IRR?', '["300% — the total return","Approximately 26% — the compound annual growth rate of capital","50% — the simple average annual return","16.7% — the total return divided by the holding period"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For a single entry and single exit: IRR = (€200/€50)^(1/6) – 1 = (4.0)^0.167 – 1 = approximately 26%. This compound return reflects that €50M growing to €200M over 6 years requires compounding at about 26% annually. A simple ''total return divided by years'' calculation (which gives 50%) is mathematically wrong because it ignores compounding.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund deploys €100M into an investment. After two years it exits for €180M. What is the IRR?', '["Approximately 34% — reflecting the compound return over two years","80% — the total return percentage","40% — the simple average","1.8x — return multiple only"]'::jsonb, 0, 'IRR = (€180/€100)^(1/2) – 1 = (1.8)^0.5 – 1 = 34.2%. This shorter hold generates higher IRR than a longer hold with the same money multiple because compounding is front-loaded. Note the same 1.8x MOIC over 4 years would be just 15.8% IRR. Time sensitivity is central to IRR''s usefulness and limitations.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund has an MOIC of 2.5x. What does this specifically mean?', '["The fund earned 250% annual returns","The fund generated $2.50 in total value for every $1.00 invested (on a gross basis, before fees and carry if reported at the deal level)","The fund''s IRR is 2.5% annually","The fund operates 2.5 times larger than its peers"]'::jsonb, 1, 'MOIC (Multiple on Invested Capital) measures total value returned as a multiple of capital invested. An MOIC of 2.5x means $1 invested returned $2.50 in total — $1 of capital returned plus $1.50 of profit. MOIC does not account for time — a 2.5x over 3 years and a 2.5x over 10 years look identical on MOIC but very different on IRR.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'At the fund level, TVPI and MOIC can differ. What''s the difference between these two metrics?', '["They are identical and often used interchangeably","TVPI (Total Value to Paid-In) measures all value including unrealised NAV against paid-in capital; MOIC at the fund level conceptually measures total distributions plus residual value against invested capital — the terms are often used synonymously","TVPI only measures cash distributions","MOIC excludes management fees"]'::jsonb, 1, 'At the fund level, TVPI and MOIC are often used synonymously: both measure total value (cash distributions plus current NAV of unrealised investments) against invested or paid-in capital. Some industry conventions distinguish them slightly, but for practical purposes LPs use TVPI when discussing fund-level performance. TVPI = DPI + RVPI captures both realised and unrealised components.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An LP''s statement shows a fund with DPI of 1.5x. What does this tell the LP about their capital?', '["The fund has lost 50% of their capital","For every €1 the LP contributed, they have received €1.50 back in actual cash distributions — they are fully capital-returned plus 50% in realised profit","The fund is worth 1.5 times its original size","The LP owes the GP additional capital"]'::jsonb, 1, 'DPI (Distributions to Paid-In) measures cash actually returned divided by cash contributed. DPI of 1.5x means the LP has received full capital back plus 50% profit in realised distributions — cash in hand, not paper value. A DPI above 1.0x means the LP is ''house money'' beyond this point. DPI is the most reliable performance metric because it cannot be inflated by optimistic NAV marks.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund reports TVPI of 2.0x at year 6, with DPI of 0.8x and RVPI of 1.2x. What does this tell an LP?', '["The fund has fully distributed all its value","The fund has returned 80% of invested capital as cash, with 120% of invested capital remaining as unrealised paper value that still needs to be exited","The LP has lost money","The GP has stolen money"]'::jsonb, 1, 'RVPI (Residual Value to Paid-In) = unrealised NAV / invested capital. TVPI = DPI + RVPI. Here: the LP has received 0.8x in cash distributions (DPI) and holds 1.2x in unrealised portfolio value (RVPI). Total paper value is 2.0x but only 40% is realised. As the fund matures, RVPI should convert to DPI through exits; failure to convert signals either delayed exits or overly optimistic valuations.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund has achieved DPI of 2.5x in year 8. What does this signal about the fund''s performance quality?', '["The fund has likely underperformed benchmark expectations","Strong realised performance — LPs have recovered 2.5x their capital in cash, a hallmark of a successful fund","The fund has returned too much too quickly","DPI of 2.5x is impossible"]'::jsonb, 1, 'DPI of 2.5x by year 8 is exceptional — LPs have received 2.5x their invested capital in cash, already exceeding most fund targets on a pure distributed basis. This is ''realised'' performance, not paper value, and is the most reliable indicator of true fund success. Any remaining RVPI adds to total return. DPI of 2.5x+ by year 8-10 is characteristic of top-decile funds.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An LP is comparing two fund reports. Fund X shows TVPI of 1.8x with DPI of 0.3x in year 9. Fund Y shows TVPI of 1.8x with DPI of 1.5x in year 9. How should the LP interpret this?', '["The funds have identical performance because TVPI is the same","Fund Y is far more credible — its TVPI is 83% realised versus Fund X''s 17% realised; Fund X carries substantial unrealised value that may be optimistically marked","Fund X is performing better because it still has more value to realise","TVPI differences are more important than DPI differences"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Same TVPI, very different quality. Fund Y has delivered most of its reported value as actual cash. Fund X''s TVPI depends heavily on unrealised marks that must still be achieved through exits — by year 9, this is concerning. A fund late in its life with large unrealised RVPI may have valuation issues, weak exit markets, or holding problem assets that cannot be marketed. LPs discount TVPI by DPI share when evaluating aged funds.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A sophisticated LP evaluates PE fund performance against a Public Market Equivalent (PME) using the Kaplan-Schoar method. What is the output, and how is it interpreted?', '["A dollar amount of outperformance","A multiple where 1.0x means PE matched the public index return; greater than 1.0x means PE outperformed, less means underperformed — on equivalent cash flows","The fund''s beta coefficient","A required investment amount"]'::jsonb, 1, 'KS-PME (Kaplan-Schoar PME) treats the public index as if it received the same capital calls and the same distribution timings as the PE fund. Output is a multiple: 1.2x means PE generated 20% more value than the public index would have on equivalent cash flows. Well-performing PE funds typically show PME of 1.1-1.3x; benchmarks below 1.0x suggest the LP would have been better off in the public index.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An LP complains that the fund''s published 18% IRR is ''inflated'' by the use of a subscription credit line. What is the concern?', '["Subscription lines charge excessive fees that reduce actual returns","Subscription lines defer LP capital calls — the fund borrows against LP commitments to fund investments, shortening the period capital is ''in'' and mathematically boosting IRR without improving underlying performance","Subscription lines are illegal","Subscription lines only affect MOIC, not IRR"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Subscription credit facilities let the GP fund investments with short-term borrowing before calling LP capital. Because IRR is time-sensitive, delaying when LP capital is ''deployed'' mathematically boosts IRR (same dollar return over a shorter period). MOIC is unaffected. An 18% IRR with sub-lines might be only 14% without. Sophisticated LPs increasingly demand pre-sub-line IRR disclosure.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm''s Fund III has achieved a realised gross IRR of 35% with MOIC of 2.8x, placing it above the 90th percentile of its vintage. What term describes this performance?', '["Median","Top-decile — the fund is among the top 10% of comparable funds by performance","Bottom-quartile","Benchmark-matching"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Percentile rankings describe performance relative to a peer group of similar-vintage funds. Top-decile = top 10% of funds; top-quartile = top 25%; median = 50th percentile; bottom-quartile = bottom 25%. Top-decile performance is the aspiration for most GPs and the primary draw for sophisticated LPs who concentrate capital with consistent outperformers. Benchmarks are published by Cambridge Associates, Preqin, Burgiss, and Pitchbook.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An institutional LP allocates exclusively to ''top-quartile'' PE managers. What does top-quartile mean, and why does this benchmark matter?', '["Top-quartile means the largest 25% of funds by AUM","Top-quartile funds outperform 75% of their peers in a comparable vintage year cohort; the benchmark matters because PE returns are highly dispersed — the gap between top and bottom quartile often exceeds 20 percentage points of IRR","Top-quartile funds are the oldest 25%","Top-quartile has no accepted definition"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Top-quartile funds rank in the top 25% of their vintage year cohort by IRR or MOIC. This benchmark matters enormously because PE returns are highly dispersed: top-quartile funds may return 2.5x+ MOIC while bottom-quartile funds return barely above 1.0x. Manager selection is the primary driver of LP returns in PE — far more than asset allocation. This is why sophisticated LPs invest heavily in GP due diligence.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A fund''s ''cash-on-cash'' return is often discussed in PE. What does this measure?', '["The annual dividend yield on portfolio companies","The ratio of cash returned to cash invested, effectively synonymous with MOIC for realised deals","The interest rate on fund-level debt","The ratio of cash to total fund assets"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cash-on-cash return is the multiple of cash returned to cash invested — effectively the same as MOIC for fully realised deals. A 2.5x cash-on-cash return means every $1 invested returned $2.50 in cash. The term emphasises physical cash flows rather than paper returns. Investors use it interchangeably with money multiple or MOIC, especially for real estate and project investments.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund''s return distribution across 20 portfolio companies shows 2 ''home runs'' (5-10x MOIC), 10 solid performers (1.5-3x MOIC), 6 break-even deals (around 1.0x MOIC), and 2 losses (below 1.0x). How does this distribution compare to typical PE fund outcomes?', '["Unusually concentrated in losses — most funds have no money-losing deals","Representative of typical PE dispersion — a small number of outperformers drive disproportionate total returns, with roughly 15-25% of deals losing money in typical funds","Unusually high-performing — most funds have no home runs","Typical funds deliver uniform 2.0x returns across all deals"]'::jsonb, 1, 'This distribution mirrors typical PE fund patterns: a small number of home runs drive disproportionate total returns (the ''Pareto'' pattern), a cluster of solid middle performers, and 15-25% of deals either break even or lose money. Even top-quartile funds typically include loss-making investments. Fund performance depends heavily on avoiding total write-offs while producing 1-2 exceptional outcomes per 10-15 deals.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A fund''s Net Asset Value (NAV) is used to calculate unrealised RVPI. How is NAV typically determined for portfolio companies?', '["By the market price if the company is publicly traded","By quarterly valuations using DCF, comparable company multiples, and precedent transaction analysis, reviewed by auditors and increasingly by valuation committees","By the original purchase price throughout the hold","By the GP''s personal judgment without methodology"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Unrealised portfolio companies are valued quarterly using a combination of methods: comparable public company trading multiples, precedent M&A transaction multiples, DCF for companies with stable cash flows, and cost for very recent investments. Valuations are reviewed by external auditors and, in many funds, by dedicated valuation committees. Despite rigorous processes, unrealised NAV carries genuine uncertainty — two GPs can reach materially different valuations for the same business.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm''s exit produces a 3.2x MOIC over 5 years. Return attribution analysis shows the breakdown: 45% from EBITDA growth, 25% from multiple expansion, 20% from debt paydown, 10% from other factors. What does this attribution tell us about the deal''s quality?', '["The deal is fundamentally flawed because returns depend on multiple drivers","The deal demonstrates balanced, high-quality value creation — driven substantially by operational improvement (EBITDA growth) rather than relying on market-driven factors like multiple expansion","The attribution indicates pure luck","The deal relied too heavily on debt paydown"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Strong, balanced attribution is characteristic of high-quality PE deals. EBITDA growth (45%) reflects operational value creation by the GP and management — repeatable and defensible. Multiple expansion (25%) reflects exit environment. Debt paydown (20%) captures financial engineering. A deal heavily dependent on a single lever (especially multiple expansion) is fragile; a balanced attribution indicates the deal would have worked even if one lever disappointed.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm''s deal generates a 4.0x MOIC over 5 years, but the attribution shows 80% came from multiple expansion (entry at 8x, exit at 14x) and only 20% from operational improvement. How should this result be interpreted?', '["It is a strong result that reflects excellent GP skill","The return is satisfying but raises concerns about repeatability — multiple expansion depends on market conditions outside the GP''s control, not on the GP''s operational capabilities","Multiple expansion is always the highest-quality return driver","The result demonstrates skilled financial engineering"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A 4.0x MOIC driven primarily by multiple expansion reflects favourable market conditions more than GP skill. The GP was correct about timing but the return depends on buyer competition, credit markets, and sector sentiment at exit. LPs value this less than an equivalent return driven by EBITDA growth because multiple-dependent returns are harder to repeat in future vintages. Repeatability is a core dimension of PE return quality.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund reports realised returns on five exited deals but has five more active investments. When evaluating the fund, what should an LP prioritise?', '["Only realised returns matter","Both realised and unrealised metrics, recognising that realised returns are certain while unrealised values carry mark-to-market uncertainty","Only unrealised valuations matter","The ratio of realised to unrealised deals is irrelevant"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Realised returns are certain cash flows that cannot be revised. Unrealised values are GP estimates subject to mark-to-market risk. A fund with strong realised track record and declining unrealised valuations is a warning sign. A fund with modest realised results but strong unrealised pipeline needs further investigation. LPs combine both views, weighted toward DPI as the realised component becomes larger.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An LP asks for a fund''s ''Since Inception'' IRR. Why is this metric more reliable than a single year''s reported return?', '["It is easier to calculate","It captures the full fund performance including capital call timing, distribution timing, and NAV changes, providing a cumulative view — a single-year return can be distorted by timing or NAV revisions","It is required by regulators","It excludes fees"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Since Inception IRR captures all cash flows (capital calls, distributions, current NAV) from fund launch through the reporting date. This provides a cumulative, time-weighted view of performance. Single-year returns can be distorted by the timing of calls/distributions, NAV revaluations, or one-off events. Since Inception IRR is the standard performance benchmark for PE funds.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm distributes €80M to LPs from a successful exit. Of this, the GP receives €12M as carry. What effective carry rate does this reflect assuming the carry was paid on the profit portion?', '["15% carry rate","Depending on the fund''s structure, approximately 20% carry on the €60M profit portion (€12M / €60M = 20%) if the capital returned was €20M","6% carry rate","80% carry rate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Assuming €20M was return of capital and €60M was profit, the €12M carry on €60M profit equals 20% — the standard PE carry rate. Carry is calculated on profit, not total distributions. The LP receives the remaining €48M of profit plus the €20M capital back, totalling €68M. This illustrates how carry aligns GP compensation with LP outcomes: no profit means no carry.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund''s vintage 2018 performance is benchmarked against 2018 vintage peers rather than current-year comparables. Why is vintage-year benchmarking critical?', '["Benchmarks are always arbitrary","PE performance is heavily dependent on entry conditions (multiples, credit availability, market cycle) — comparing funds of different vintages mixes very different underlying environments","Vintage year only matters for tax purposes","LPs cannot access vintage-year benchmarks"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Vintage matters because PE performance is heavily shaped by entry conditions. 2009-vintage funds (deploying post-crisis at low multiples) typically outperform 2007-vintage funds (deploying at peak multiples). Comparing a 2018 fund to 2022 funds would mix very different entry environments. Vintage-year benchmarks — Cambridge Associates, Preqin, Burgiss — cluster funds by the year they began deploying and provide percentile rankings within that cohort.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'Cambridge Associates, Preqin, and Burgiss are three prominent sources of PE benchmark data. What do they provide?', '["They provide capital directly to PE funds","They aggregate performance data from hundreds of funds to produce vintage-year benchmarks, showing median, top-quartile, and other percentile return thresholds that LPs use for comparison","They regulate PE fund performance","They audit PE fund returns"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Cambridge Associates, Preqin, Burgiss (now part of MSCI), and Pitchbook aggregate performance data from hundreds of PE funds to produce vintage-year benchmarks. Outputs include median, top-quartile, and other percentile thresholds for IRR, MOIC, TVPI, and DPI. Their data is used by LPs for benchmarking, investment committee presentations, and allocation decisions. Each uses slightly different methodologies and fund samples, producing subtle benchmark variations.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE portfolio company with €20M EBITDA is sold for €200M. Entry had been €160M (10x EBITDA of €16M). During the hold, €40M of debt was repaid. Original equity was €60M. What equity value is realised at exit, and what MOIC is generated?', '["€140M equity, 2.3x MOIC","€200M equity, 3.3x MOIC","€180M equity, 3.0x MOIC","€60M equity, 1.0x MOIC"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Entry: €160M EV with €60M equity + €100M debt. Exit: €200M EV with remaining debt of €60M (€100M original – €40M paid down). Exit equity = €200M – €60M = €140M. MOIC = €140M / €60M = 2.33x. Even without EBITDA growth (€20M vs entry €16M = modest growth), debt paydown and some EBITDA increase produced a 2.3x equity return.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm quotes a ''gross deal IRR'' of 32% but the ''fund net IRR'' is 18%. Which represents what the LP actually earns and what factors cause the gap?', '["Gross deal IRR is what LPs earn; the fund net IRR is a theoretical number","Fund net IRR (18%) is what LPs actually earn after management fees, carry, fund expenses, and the J-curve effect of fund cash flow timing; the gap is typical 10-15 percentage points for well-performing funds","Gross and net IRR are always identical for sophisticated funds","The gap only reflects taxes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Fund net IRR is what LPs actually earn — the true measure of LP experience. The gap (here 14 percentage points) reflects: management fees (reduce invested capital base), carried interest (reduces LP share of profits), fund expenses (audit, legal, operational), and the J-curve (time between LP capital calls and eventual distributions). Well-performing funds typically have 3-7 percentage point gap; this 14-point gap may reflect expensive fee structure or subscription line effects on gross IRR.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'An LP is evaluating whether a 2.2x MOIC over 7 years meets their return hurdle. What IRR does this approximately represent?', '["Approximately 31%","Approximately 12%","Approximately 22%","Approximately 2%"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IRR = (2.2)^(1/7) – 1 = approximately 11.9%. A 2.2x over 7 years compounds at about 12% annually. This illustrates that MOIC must always be contextualised with the hold period to calculate the true return: 2.2x over 3 years is 30% IRR, over 5 years is 17% IRR, over 7 years is 12% IRR. Longer holds compress IRR even when MOIC is identical.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund exits a portfolio company for €300M. The fund''s cash flow history for this deal shows a €100M investment at year 0, a €30M dividend recapitalisation at year 3, and the €300M exit at year 5. How does the interim dividend affect returns compared to a pure hold-and-exit?', '["It has no effect on IRR","The interim distribution at year 3 boosts IRR by shortening the effective time-weighted capital exposure, even though total MOIC increases only modestly","It reduces IRR because it delays the final exit","It has no effect on MOIC"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Interim distributions significantly boost IRR. Without dividend: €100M → €300M over 5 years = 24.6% IRR, 3.0x MOIC. With €30M dividend at year 3 plus €300M exit: MOIC = 3.3x (€330M total / €100M), IRR approximately 27-28%. The interim cash flow reduces capital-at-risk time, accelerating the calculated return. This is why dividend recapitalisations are popular with GPs — they enhance reported IRR.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund reports ''realised IRR'' of 28% on fully exited deals but ''total fund IRR'' of 18% including unrealised positions. What does this comparison suggest?', '["The fund has been manipulating returns","The fund has successfully exited its best deals first, leaving weaker performers in the remaining portfolio — a phenomenon sometimes called ''cream skimming'' or natural exit order","The fund has underperformed","The two metrics are unrelated"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Large gaps between realised and total fund IRR often indicate that strong deals exit first (either because strong businesses sell more easily, or because GPs rationally harvest winners quickly) while weaker deals linger. Sophisticated LPs analyse the trajectory: is the gap narrowing as more exits occur, or widening? A persistent gap suggests unrealised positions are overvalued or the remaining portfolio is genuinely weaker than early exits.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund generates a 25% gross IRR over 5 years. During that time, the S&P 500 generates 12% annualised. The fund''s KS-PME is 1.35x. What does this tell us?', '["The fund underperformed the S&P 500","The fund generated $1.35 for every $1.00 that an S&P investment would have returned on the same cash flow schedule — meaningful outperformance that captures the ''alpha'' above public market beta","The fund outperformed by 35 percentage points","PME does not apply to buyout funds"]'::jsonb, 1, 'PME of 1.35x indicates the fund outperformed the S&P by 35% in total value terms across the same cash flow schedule. This captures true ''alpha'' — returns above what a passive public index position would have delivered on equivalent capital timing. Strong PME (typically 1.1-1.3x) is the benchmark that sophisticated LPs increasingly demand. A 25% IRR during a strong bull market without corresponding PME outperformance suggests beta rather than alpha.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE firm produces a fund-level performance bridge for LP reporting. Which components typically break down total fund value creation?', '["Only EBITDA growth","EBITDA growth (operational improvement), multiple change (market expansion/compression), leverage/debt paydown, FX effects (for international investments), and dividend distributions during hold","Only management fee rebates","Only inflation adjustments"]'::jsonb, 1, 'A value creation bridge decomposes total fund return: (1) EBITDA growth — what operational improvement added; (2) Multiple change — market-driven valuation shifts; (3) Debt paydown — leverage amplification; (4) FX effects for international deals; (5) Interim distributions during hold. This analysis reveals the source of returns and tests whether success is driven by skill (operational improvement) or market conditions (multiple expansion), affecting how LPs assess repeatability.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund''s realised track record shows MOIC of 2.5x, IRR of 20%, and DPI of 2.0x by year 8. A new LP is evaluating whether to commit to the GP''s next fund. What aspect of this track record is most important for the LP''s decision?', '["Only the IRR matters for fund selection","The consistency, repeatability, and attribution behind these returns — not just the headline numbers — because past performance only predicts future results if the team, strategy, and market conditions remain comparable","Only the MOIC matters","Only the DPI matters"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Strong return metrics are necessary but insufficient. LPs investigate: Is the team stable? Are returns concentrated in a few outlier deals or broadly distributed? What drove returns (skill vs. market conditions)? Has the strategy changed? Does the fund size growth maintain focus? Superior historical returns with a departed team, changed strategy, or concentration in one lucky deal do not predict future outperformance. GP due diligence goes far beyond the headline numbers.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A pension fund''s PE portfolio has a Target Date Weighted IRR of 14% (across all funds in its portfolio). What does this aggregate metric measure?', '["A measure of retirement savings timing","The combined IRR across all PE fund commitments in the LP''s portfolio, weighted by capital deployed and duration — the LP''s actual PE-asset-class return","Only the most recent fund''s IRR","A theoretical calculation unrelated to actual returns"]'::jsonb, 1, 'At the LP portfolio level, the Target Date Weighted IRR (or ''portfolio IRR'') aggregates returns across all fund commitments, weighted by capital invested and time. This represents the LP''s actual asset-class return. The pension fund aggregates this across all its LP positions to determine whether PE has delivered against its target allocation. This aggregate perspective differs from fund-level IRRs because portfolio construction (vintage diversification, manager mix) affects total returns.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund''s LPA defines carry on an 8% preferred return. If the fund generates an 8% IRR, what carry does the GP earn?', '["20% of all fund profits","Zero — the GP only earns carry on returns above the preferred hurdle; an 8% IRR exactly meets (but does not exceed) the preferred return","8% of fund profits","The carry is double"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Carry only applies to returns above the preferred return hurdle. If the fund generates exactly 8% IRR (meeting the preferred return), there is no excess profit to split — GP earns zero carry. This ''underwater'' scenario sometimes occurs in weaker funds or vintages. LPs in this situation receive the 8% preferred return but no additional distributions. This structural feature protects LPs from paying carry on mediocre performance.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'A PE fund''s annualised return during a bull market was 22% IRR; during a subsequent downturn, reported valuations declined. If no exits occurred during the downturn, what typically happens to reported IRR?', '["IRR remains unchanged without exits","Reported IRR decreases as unrealised NAV is marked down, even without any realised losses — because IRR calculations include current NAV as a terminal value","IRR increases automatically","The fund must terminate"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IRR calculations for live funds use current NAV as a ''terminal value'' for unrealised positions. When market conditions decline, NAVs are typically reduced through lower multiple assumptions or EBITDA revisions, which reduces reported IRR even without any realised losses. This is why interim IRR is volatile and why sophisticated LPs focus on DPI (realised returns) as the more stable indicator. Realised IRR only changes with exits; total fund IRR moves with NAV revisions.'),
  ('4d355fb9-493f-4101-9a9f-bc7ec6f85ca6', 'return-metrics', 'Why do sophisticated LPs evaluate both IRR and MOIC when selecting PE funds, rather than focusing on either one alone?', '["Because both metrics always produce the same conclusion","Because IRR captures time sensitivity (a better measure of capital efficiency) while MOIC captures total value creation (a better measure of absolute return); using only one can misrank funds","Because regulators require both to be reported","Because only MOIC matters for fund selection"]'::jsonb, 1, 'IRR and MOIC answer different questions. IRR asks: how efficiently was capital deployed in time? MOIC asks: how much value did each dollar produce? A 30% IRR over 2 years (1.7x MOIC) is different from a 20% IRR over 7 years (3.6x MOIC) — both excellent but for different reasons. LPs use both: IRR for capital efficiency and compounding assessment, MOIC for total value creation. Using one alone can misrank funds with different hold periods.')
